<!DOCTYPE html>

<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8"/>
<meta content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" name="viewport"/>
<title>Qualitative Evidenzsynthese: Das Warum verstehen</title>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" rel="preconnect"/>
<link crossorigin="" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" rel="preconnect"/>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Cormorant+Garamond:ital,wght@0,400;0,600;0,700;1,400;1,600&amp;family=Source+Sans+Pro:wght@300;400;600;700&amp;display=swap" rel="stylesheet"/>
<style>
    :root {
      --navy: #1E2761;
      --deep-navy: #141B3D;
      --gold: #D4AF37;
      --cream: #FAF8F5;
      --light-cream: #FFFFFF;
      --text: #2D3748;
      --light-text: #718096;
      --red: #C53030;
      --green: #22c55e;
      --teal: #0f766e;
      --purple: #7c3aed;
      --orange: #f59e0b;
      --transition: 0.5s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
    }

    * { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
    html, body {
      height: 100%;
      font-family: 'Source Sans Pro', sans-serif;
      background: var(--deep-navy);
      color: var(--cream);
    }

    .course-container { display: flex; height: 100vh; overflow: hidden; }

    /* Skip Link */
    .skip-link {
      position: absolute;
      top: -40px;
      left: 0;
      background: var(--gold);
      color: var(--navy);
      padding: 8px 16px;
      z-index: 10000;
      text-decoration: none;
      font-weight: 600;
    }
    .skip-link:focus { top: 0; }

    /* Sidebar */
    .sidebar {
      width: 300px;
      background: linear-gradient(180deg, var(--deep-navy) 0%, #0a0f1a 100%);
      border-right: 1px solid rgba(212,175,55,0.2);
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      flex-shrink: 0;
    }

    .sidebar-header {
      padding: 1.25rem;
      border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(212,175,55,0.2);
      text-align: center;
    }
    .sidebar-header h1 {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', Georgia, serif;
      font-size: 1.2rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: var(--gold);
    }
    .sidebar-header p {
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);
    }

    .stats-panel {
      padding: 1rem;
      background: rgba(212,175,55,0.1);
      border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(212,175,55,0.2);
    }
    .level-display {
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    }
    .level-badge {
      width: 48px;
      height: 48px;
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--gold), #f0c040);
      border-radius: 50%;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      font-size: 1.5rem;
      box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(212,175,55,0.4);
    }
    .level-info { flex: 1; }
    .level-title { font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--gold); }
    .level-subtitle { font-size: 0.7rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6); }
    .xp-bar {
      height: 8px;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
      border-radius: 4px;
      overflow: hidden;
      margin-top: 0.5rem;
    }
    .xp-fill {
      height: 100%;
      background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--gold), var(--orange));
      border-radius: 4px;
      transition: width 0.5s ease;
    }
    .xp-text {
      font-size: 0.65rem;
      color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5);
      text-align: right;
      margin-top: 0.25rem;
    }
    .quick-stats {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
      gap: 0.5rem;
      margin-top: 0.75rem;
    }
    .quick-stat {
      background: rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
      padding: 0.5rem;
      border-radius: 6px;
      text-align: center;
    }
    .quick-stat-value {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: var(--gold);
    }
    .quick-stat-label {
      font-size: 0.6rem;
      color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5);
    }

    .course-progress {
      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
      border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(212,175,55,0.2);
      background: rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
    }
    .course-progress-label {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-between;
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);
      margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
    }
    .course-progress-bar {
      height: 6px;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
      border-radius: 3px;
      overflow: hidden;
    }
    .course-progress-fill {
      height: 100%;
      background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--green), #22d3ee);
      border-radius: 3px;
      transition: width 0.5s ease;
    }

    .module-list { flex: 1; overflow-y: auto; padding: 0.5rem 0; }
    .module-item {
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      padding: 0.6rem 1rem;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: all 0.2s;
      border-left: 3px solid transparent;
    }
    .module-item:hover { background: rgba(212,175,55,0.1); }
    .module-item.active { background: rgba(212,175,55,0.15); border-left-color: var(--gold); }
    .module-item.completed .module-number { background: var(--green); color: white; }
    .module-item.locked { opacity: 0.5; cursor: not-allowed; }
    .module-number {
      width: 26px;
      height: 26px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      flex-shrink: 0;
    }
    .module-item.active .module-number { background: var(--gold); color: var(--navy); }
    .module-info { flex: 1; min-width: 0; }
    .module-title { font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 600; white-space: nowrap; overflow: hidden; text-overflow: ellipsis; }
    .module-subtitle { font-size: 0.65rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5); }
    .module-xp { font-size: 0.6rem; color: var(--gold); }
    .module-time { font-size: 0.55rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.4); display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.25rem; margin-top: 0.15rem; }

    .badges-panel {
      padding: 1rem;
      border-top: 1px solid rgba(212,175,55,0.2);
    }
    .badges-title { font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--gold); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .badges-grid { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.35rem; }
    .badge-item {
      width: 32px;
      height: 32px;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05);
      border: 2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
      border-radius: 6px;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      opacity: 0.3;
      transition: all 0.3s;
      cursor: help;
      position: relative;
    }
    .badge-item.earned { opacity: 1; background: rgba(212,175,55,0.2); border-color: var(--gold); }
    .badge-item:hover::after {
      content: attr(data-tooltip);
      position: absolute;
      bottom: 100%;
      left: 50%;
      transform: translateX(-50%);
      background: var(--navy);
      color: white;
      padding: 0.25rem 0.5rem;
      border-radius: 4px;
      font-size: 0.6rem;
      white-space: nowrap;
      z-index: 100;
    }

    /* Main Content */
    .main-content { flex: 1; display: flex; flex-direction: column; overflow: hidden; }
    .content-header {
      padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem;
      background: rgba(0,0,0,0.3);
      border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(212,175,55,0.2);
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: space-between;
    }
    .breadcrumb { font-size: 0.85rem; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6); }
    .breadcrumb span { color: var(--gold); }
    .header-actions { display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; align-items: center; }
    .streak-display {
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.35rem;
      background: rgba(239,68,68,0.2);
      border: 1px solid rgba(239,68,68,0.4);
      padding: 0.35rem 0.75rem;
      border-radius: 20px;
      font-size: 0.8rem;
    }
    .streak-display.active { background: rgba(249,115,22,0.2); border-color: var(--orange); }
    .streak-flame { font-size: 1rem; }
    .streak-count { font-weight: 700; color: var(--orange); }

    .btn {
      padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
      border: 1px solid rgba(212,175,55,0.3);
      border-radius: 6px;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05);
      color: var(--cream);
      font-size: 0.8rem;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: all 0.2s;
    }
    .btn:hover { background: rgba(212,175,55,0.2); border-color: var(--gold); }
    .btn.primary { background: var(--gold); color: var(--navy); border-color: var(--gold); font-weight: 600; }

    .content-body { flex: 1; overflow: hidden; display: flex; }

    /* Slides */
    .slides-container { flex: 1; position: relative; overflow: hidden; }
    .module-slides { display: none; width: 100%; height: 100%; }
    .module-slides.active { display: block; }

    .slide {
      position: absolute;
      top: 0; left: 0;
      width: 100%; height: 100%;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      justify-content: flex-start;
      align-items: center;
      padding: 2rem 2rem 4rem;
      opacity: 0;
      visibility: hidden;
      transition: opacity var(--transition), visibility var(--transition);
      overflow-y: auto;
    }
    .slide.active { opacity: 1; visibility: visible; }
    .slide.dark { background: var(--deep-navy); }
    .slide.light { background: var(--cream); color: var(--text); }
    .slide.black { background: #000; }
    .slide.red-bg { background: linear-gradient(135deg, #7f1d1d, #450a0a); }
    .slide.green-bg { background: linear-gradient(135deg, #14532d, #052e16); }
    .slide.purple-bg { background: linear-gradient(135deg, #4c1d95, #2e1065); }
    .slide.orange-bg { background: linear-gradient(135deg, #9a3412, #431407); }
    .slide.teal-bg { background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0f766e, #042f2e); }

    .slide-progress-bar {
      position: absolute;
      top: 0;
      left: 0;
      height: 3px;
      background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--gold), var(--orange));
      transition: width 0.3s ease;
      z-index: 50;
    }

    .serif { font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', Georgia, serif; }
    .title {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', Georgia, serif;
      font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 4vw, 3rem);
      font-weight: 700;
      margin-bottom: 1rem;
      line-height: 1.2;
      text-align: center;
    }
    .title.gold { color: var(--gold); }
    .title.navy { color: var(--navy); }
    .subtitle {
      font-size: clamp(0.9rem, 2vw, 1.3rem);
      color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7);
      margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
      text-align: center;
    }
    .slide.light .subtitle { color: var(--light-text); }

    .big-number {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', Georgia, serif;
      font-size: clamp(4rem, 12vw, 8rem);
      font-weight: 700;
      line-height: 1;
    }
    .big-number.gold { color: var(--gold); }
    .big-number.red { color: var(--red); }

    .refrain {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', Georgia, serif;
      font-size: clamp(1.3rem, 3vw, 2rem);
      font-style: italic;
      color: var(--gold);
      text-align: center;
      max-width: 700px;
    }

    .content { display: flex; flex-direction: column; align-items: center; width: 100%; max-width: 850px; }

    /* Cards */
    .card {
      background: var(--light-cream);
      border: 1px solid var(--gold);
      padding: 1.25rem 1.5rem;
      margin: 0.5rem 0;
      max-width: 750px;
      width: 100%;
      border-radius: 8px;
    }
    .card.navy-bg { background: var(--navy); color: var(--cream); }
    .card-label {
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: var(--gold);
      letter-spacing: 0.05em;
      margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
      text-transform: uppercase;
    }
    .card-text { font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; }
    .card.navy-bg .card-text { color: var(--cream); }

    /* Story box */
    .story-box {
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(197,48,48,0.15), rgba(30,39,97,0.2));
      border-left: 4px solid var(--red);
      padding: 1.25rem;
      margin: 0.75rem 0;
      max-width: 750px;
      width: 100%;
      border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0;
    }
    .story-box.success { background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(34,197,94,0.15), rgba(30,39,97,0.2)); border-left-color: var(--green); }
    .story-box.warning { background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(245,158,11,0.15), rgba(30,39,97,0.2)); border-left-color: var(--orange); }
    .story-box.teal { background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(15,118,110,0.15), rgba(30,39,97,0.2)); border-left-color: var(--teal); }
    .story-label {
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      letter-spacing: 0.1em;
      color: var(--red);
      margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
      text-transform: uppercase;
    }
    .story-box.success .story-label { color: var(--green); }
    .story-box.warning .story-label { color: var(--orange); }
    .story-box.teal .story-label { color: var(--teal); }
    .story-text { font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; }

    /* CERQual Confidence Colors */
    .cerqual-high { background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(34,197,94,0.2), rgba(30,39,97,0.2)); border-color: var(--green); }
    .cerqual-moderate { background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(59,130,246,0.2), rgba(30,39,97,0.2)); border-color: #3b82f6; }
    .cerqual-low { background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(245,158,11,0.2), rgba(30,39,97,0.2)); border-color: var(--orange); }
    .cerqual-very-low { background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(197,48,48,0.2), rgba(30,39,97,0.2)); border-color: var(--red); }

    .cerqual-badge {
      display: inline-block;
      padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem;
      border-radius: 4px;
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    }
    .cerqual-badge.high { background: var(--green); color: white; }
    .cerqual-badge.moderate { background: #3b82f6; color: white; }
    .cerqual-badge.low { background: var(--orange); color: white; }
    .cerqual-badge.very-low { background: var(--red); color: white; }

    /* Stats */
    .stats-grid {
      display: flex;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      margin: 1rem 0;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      justify-content: center;
    }
    .stat-box {
      background: var(--navy);
      color: var(--cream);
      padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
      text-align: center;
      min-width: 120px;
      border-radius: 8px;
    }
    .stat-value {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
      font-size: clamp(1.3rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);
      font-weight: 700;
    }
    .stat-value.gold { color: var(--gold); }
    .stat-value.red { color: var(--red); }
    .stat-value.green { color: var(--green); }
    .stat-label { font-size: 0.75rem; opacity: 0.8; margin-top: 0.2rem; }

    /* Timeline */
    .timeline { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.4rem; width: 100%; max-width: 650px; }
    .timeline-item {
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05);
      border-radius: 6px;
      border-left: 4px solid var(--gold);
    }
    .timeline-days { font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.8rem; min-width: 70px; color: var(--gold); }
    .timeline-content { flex: 1; }
    .timeline-title { font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.9rem; }
    .timeline-desc { font-size: 0.75rem; opacity: 0.7; }

    /* Checklist */
    .checklist { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.4rem; width: 100%; max-width: 650px; }
    .checklist-item {
      display: flex;
      align-items: flex-start;
      gap: 0.6rem;
      padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05);
      border-radius: 6px;
      border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
    }
    .check-icon {
      width: 20px;
      height: 20px;
      background: var(--green);
      border-radius: 50%;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      color: white;
      flex-shrink: 0;
    }
    .checklist-text { font-size: 0.9rem; }

    /* Decision Tree */
    .decision-tree {
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(124,58,237,0.1), rgba(30,39,97,0.2));
      border: 2px solid var(--purple);
      border-radius: 12px;
      padding: 1.25rem;
      width: 100%;
      max-width: 700px;
    }
    .decision-header {
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      margin-bottom: 1rem;
    }
    .decision-icon {
      width: 40px;
      height: 40px;
      background: var(--purple);
      border-radius: 50%;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      font-size: 1.25rem;
    }
    .decision-title {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
      font-size: 1.2rem;
      font-weight: 700;
    }
    .decision-xp {
      margin-left: auto;
      background: rgba(212,175,55,0.2);
      padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem;
      border-radius: 12px;
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      color: var(--gold);
      font-weight: 600;
    }
    .decision-scenario {
      background: rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
      padding: 1rem;
      border-radius: 8px;
      margin-bottom: 1rem;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }
    .decision-question {
      font-weight: 600;
      color: var(--gold);
      margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
      font-size: 1rem;
    }
    .decision-options { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; }
    .decision-option {
      display: flex;
      align-items: flex-start;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05);
      border: 2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.15);
      border-radius: 8px;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: all 0.2s;
    }
    .decision-option:hover { background: rgba(124,58,237,0.2); border-color: var(--purple); }
    .decision-option.selected { background: rgba(124,58,237,0.3); border-color: var(--purple); }
    .decision-option.correct { background: rgba(34,197,94,0.2); border-color: var(--green); }
    .decision-option.incorrect { background: rgba(239,68,68,0.15); border-color: var(--red); }
    .decision-option.disabled { pointer-events: none; opacity: 0.7; }
    .decision-option:focus-visible { outline: 3px solid var(--gold); outline-offset: 2px; }
    .option-letter {
      width: 24px;
      height: 24px;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
      border-radius: 50%;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      font-weight: 700;
      font-size: 0.8rem;
      flex-shrink: 0;
    }
    .decision-option.correct .option-letter { background: var(--green); color: white; }
    .decision-option.incorrect .option-letter { background: var(--red); color: white; }
    .option-text { font-size: 0.9rem; }
    .decision-feedback {
      margin-top: 1rem;
      padding: 1rem;
      border-radius: 8px;
      display: none;
    }
    .decision-feedback.show { display: block; }
    .decision-feedback.correct { background: rgba(34,197,94,0.2); border: 1px solid var(--green); }
    .decision-feedback.incorrect { background: rgba(239,68,68,0.15); border: 1px solid var(--red); }
    .feedback-title { font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .feedback-text { font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.5; }

    /* Quiz */
    .quiz-container { width: 100%; max-width: 650px; }
    .quiz-question {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
      font-size: 1.2rem;
      margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
      text-align: center;
    }
    .quiz-options { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; }
    .quiz-option {
      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.05);
      border: 2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2);
      border-radius: 8px;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: all 0.2s;
      text-align: left;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
    }
    .quiz-option:hover { background: rgba(212,175,55,0.15); border-color: var(--gold); }
    .quiz-option.correct { background: rgba(34,197,94,0.2); border-color: var(--green); }
    .quiz-option.incorrect { background: rgba(239,68,68,0.15); border-color: var(--red); }
    .quiz-option.disabled { pointer-events: none; }
    .quiz-option:focus-visible { outline: 3px solid var(--gold); outline-offset: 2px; }
    .quiz-feedback {
      margin-top: 1rem;
      padding: 1rem;
      border-radius: 8px;
      display: none;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
    }
    .quiz-feedback.show { display: block; }
    .quiz-feedback.correct { background: rgba(34,197,94,0.2); border: 1px solid var(--green); }
    .quiz-feedback.incorrect { background: rgba(239,68,68,0.15); border: 1px solid var(--red); }

    /* Learning Objectives */
    .objectives-box {
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(59,130,246,0.15), rgba(30,39,97,0.25));
      border: 2px solid #3b82f6;
      border-radius: 12px;
      padding: 1.25rem;
      margin: 0.75rem 0;
      max-width: 700px;
      width: 100%;
    }
    .objectives-header {
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    }
    .objectives-icon {
      width: 36px;
      height: 36px;
      background: #3b82f6;
      border-radius: 50%;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
    }
    .objectives-title {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: #60a5fa;
    }
    .objectives-list { list-style: none; padding: 0; }
    .objectives-list li {
      display: flex;
      align-items: flex-start;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      padding: 0.4rem 0;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
    }
    .objectives-list li::before { content: '○'; color: #3b82f6; font-weight: bold; }

    /* Animation */
    .slide.active .animate { animation: fadeUp 0.5s ease-out forwards; }
    .slide.active .animate.delay-1 { animation-delay: 0.1s; }
    .slide.active .animate.delay-2 { animation-delay: 0.2s; }
    .slide.active .animate.delay-3 { animation-delay: 0.3s; }
    @keyframes fadeUp {
      from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(15px); }
      to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
    }
    .animate { opacity: 0; }

    /* XP Popup */
    .xp-popup {
      position: fixed;
      top: 50%;
      left: 50%;
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%) scale(0);
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--gold), #f0c040);
      color: var(--navy);
      padding: 1.5rem 2.5rem;
      border-radius: 12px;
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
      font-size: 2rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      z-index: 1000;
      box-shadow: 0 10px 40px rgba(0,0,0,0.5);
      transition: transform 0.3s ease;
    }
    .xp-popup.show { transform: translate(-50%, -50%) scale(1); }
    .xp-popup .xp-amount { font-size: 3rem; display: block; }

    /* Badge Modal */
    .badge-modal {
      position: fixed;
      top: 0; left: 0; right: 0; bottom: 0;
      background: rgba(0,0,0,0.85);
      display: none;
      justify-content: center;
      align-items: center;
      z-index: 1001;
    }
    .badge-modal.show { display: flex; }
    .badge-modal-content {
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--deep-navy), #0a0f1a);
      border: 2px solid var(--gold);
      border-radius: 16px;
      padding: 2rem;
      text-align: center;
      max-width: 350px;
    }
    .badge-modal-icon { font-size: 4rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .badge-modal-title {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
      font-size: 1.5rem;
      color: var(--gold);
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    .badge-modal-desc { font-size: 0.9rem; opacity: 0.8; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .badge-modal-close {
      padding: 0.5rem 1.5rem;
      background: var(--gold);
      color: var(--navy);
      border: none;
      border-radius: 6px;
      font-weight: 600;
      cursor: pointer;
    }

    /* Confetti */
    .confetti-container {
      position: fixed;
      top: 0; left: 0;
      width: 100%; height: 100%;
      pointer-events: none;
      z-index: 999;
      overflow: hidden;
    }
    .confetti {
      position: absolute;
      width: 10px; height: 10px;
      opacity: 0;
      animation: confetti-fall 3s ease-out forwards;
    }
    @keyframes confetti-fall {
      0% { transform: translateY(-100px) rotate(0deg); opacity: 1; }
      100% { transform: translateY(100vh) rotate(720deg); opacity: 0; }
    }
    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      .confetti { animation: none; display: none; }
      .xp-popup { transition: none; }
      .slide { transition: none; }
    }

    /* Nav */
    .slide-nav {
      position: absolute;
      bottom: 0; left: 0; right: 0;
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-between;
      align-items: flex-end;
      padding: 0.75rem 1rem 1.25rem;
      z-index: 100;
      pointer-events: none;
    }
    .nav-btn {
      background: rgba(0,0,0,0.5);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2);
      color: white;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      cursor: pointer;
      opacity: 0.6;
      transition: all 0.2s;
      padding: 0.4rem 0.6rem;
      border-radius: 6px;
      pointer-events: auto;
    }
    .nav-btn:hover { opacity: 1; background: rgba(0,0,0,0.7); border-color: var(--gold); }
    .nav-btn:disabled { opacity: 0.2; cursor: not-allowed; }
    .nav-btn:focus-visible { outline: 3px solid var(--gold); outline-offset: 2px; }
    .nav-center { display: flex; flex-direction: column; align-items: center; gap: 0.2rem; pointer-events: auto; }
    .slide-counter { font-size: 0.7rem; opacity: 0.5; }
    .progress-dots { display: flex; gap: 3px; }
    .progress-dot {
      width: 5px; height: 5px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      background: rgba(255,255,255,0.25);
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: all 0.2s;
    }
    .progress-dot.active { background: var(--gold); transform: scale(1.3); }

    /* Mobile */
    @media (max-width: 768px) {
      .sidebar {
        position: fixed;
        left: -300px;
        top: 0;
        bottom: 0;
        z-index: 1000;
        transition: left 0.3s ease;
      }
      .sidebar.open { left: 0; }
      .sidebar-toggle {
        display: flex;
        position: fixed;
        top: 10px;
        left: 10px;
        z-index: 1001;
        width: 40px;
        height: 40px;
        background: var(--gold);
        color: var(--navy);
        border: none;
        border-radius: 8px;
        align-items: center;
        justify-content: center;
        font-size: 1.2rem;
        cursor: pointer;
      }
      .sidebar-overlay {
        display: none;
        position: fixed;
        top: 0; left: 0; right: 0; bottom: 0;
        background: rgba(0,0,0,0.5);
        z-index: 999;
      }
      .sidebar-overlay.show { display: block; }
    }
    @media (min-width: 769px) {
      .sidebar-toggle { display: none; }
      .sidebar-overlay { display: none !important; }
    }

    /* Combo Counter */
    .combo-display {
      position: fixed;
      top: 80px;
      right: 20px;
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--orange), #ef4444);
      color: white;
      padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
      border-radius: 20px;
      font-weight: 700;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      z-index: 500;
      transform: scale(0);
      transition: transform 0.3s ease;
      box-shadow: 0 4px 15px rgba(239,68,68,0.4);
    }
    .combo-display.show { transform: scale(1); }

    /* Quote Block */
    .quote-block {
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(15,118,110,0.2), rgba(30,39,97,0.2));
      border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);
      padding: 1.25rem;
      margin: 0.75rem 0;
      max-width: 700px;
      width: 100%;
      border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0;
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      font-style: italic;
    }
    .quote-attribution {
      margin-top: 0.75rem;
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      font-style: normal;
      color: var(--teal);
    }

    /* Key Takeaways */
    .takeaways-container {
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(34,197,94,0.15), rgba(30,39,97,0.2));
      border: 2px solid var(--green);
      border-radius: 12px;
      padding: 1.5rem;
      width: 100%;
      max-width: 700px;
      text-align: center;
    }
    .takeaways-icon {
      font-size: 2.5rem;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    .takeaways-title {
      font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
      font-size: 1.4rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: var(--green);
      margin-bottom: 1rem;
    }
    .takeaways-list {
      text-align: left;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      gap: 0.6rem;
    }
    .takeaway-item {
      display: flex;
      align-items: flex-start;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem;
      background: rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
      border-radius: 6px;
    }
    .takeaway-bullet {
      color: var(--green);
      font-weight: 700;
      flex-shrink: 0;
    }
    .takeaway-text {
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.5;
    }
    .takeaways-remember {
      margin-top: 1rem;
      padding: 0.75rem;
      background: rgba(212,175,55,0.15);
      border-left: 3px solid var(--gold);
      border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      text-align: left;
    }

    /* Mobile progress dots - larger touch targets */
    @media (max-width: 768px) {
      .progress-dot {
        width: 8px;
        height: 8px;
        min-width: 8px;
        min-height: 8px;
      }
      .progress-dots { gap: 6px; }
    }

    /* Print Styles */
    @media print {
      body {
        background: white;
        color: black;
        font-size: 12pt;
      }
      .sidebar, .sidebar-toggle, .sidebar-overlay,
      .xp-popup, .combo-display, .confetti-container,
      .badge-modal, .nav-btn, .progress-dots, .slide-counter,
      .header-actions, .streak-display, .content-header {
        display: none !important;
      }
      .course-container {
        display: block;
      }
      .main-content {
        width: 100%;
        max-width: 100%;
        padding: 0;
      }
      .slide {
        display: block !important;
        opacity: 1 !important;
        page-break-inside: avoid;
        margin-bottom: 2rem;
        border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
        padding-bottom: 1rem;
      }
      .story-box, .decision-tree, .quiz-container {
        background: #f5f5f5 !important;
        border-color: #333 !important;
        color: black !important;
      }
      .decision-option, .quiz-option {
        background: white !important;
        border: 1px solid #333 !important;
        color: black !important;
      }
      .decision-option.correct, .quiz-option.correct {
        background: #d4edda !important;
        border: 2px solid #28a745 !important;
      }
      .decision-option.correct::after, .quiz-option.correct::after {
        content: " ✓ CORRECT";
        font-weight: bold;
        color: #28a745;
      }
      .slide-title, .decision-title {
        color: black !important;
      }
      .decision-feedback, .quiz-feedback {
        display: block !important;
        background: #f8f9fa !important;
        border: 1px solid #333 !important;
        color: black !important;
        padding: 1rem !important;
        margin-top: 1rem !important;
      }
      .takeaways-container {
        background: #f0fff0 !important;
        border-color: #28a745 !important;
        color: black !important;
      }
      .takeaways-title {
        color: #155724 !important;
      }
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
<a class="skip-link" href="#main-content">Skip to main content</a>
<div class="course-container">
<!-- Sidebar -->
<nav aria-label="Kursnavigation" class="sidebar" role="navigation">
<div class="sidebar-header">
<a href="index.html" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(212,175,55,0.7)'" onmouseover="this.style.color='#D4AF37'" style="display:block;font-size:0.7rem;color:rgba(212,175,55,0.7);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:0.5rem;">← Course Library</a>
<h1>Qualitative Synthesis</h1>
<p>Das Warum verstehen</p>
</div>
<div class="stats-panel">
<div class="level-display">
<div class="level-badge" id="levelIcon">🎙️</div>
<div class="level-info">
<div class="level-title" id="levelTitle">Novice Listener</div>
<div class="level-subtitle">Level <span id="levelNum">1</span></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="xp-bar"><div class="xp-fill" id="xpFill" style="width: 0%"></div></div>
<div class="xp-text"><span id="xpCurrent">0</span> / <span id="xpNeeded">100</span> XP</div>
<div class="quick-stats">
<div class="quick-stat">
<div class="quick-stat-value" id="correctCount">0</div>
<div class="quick-stat-label">Correct</div>
</div>
<div class="quick-stat">
<div class="quick-stat-value" id="decisionCount">0</div>
<div class="quick-stat-label">Decisions</div>
</div>
<div class="quick-stat">
<div class="quick-stat-value" id="synthesisCount">0</div>
<div class="quick-stat-label">Synthesized</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="course-progress">
<div class="course-progress-label">
<span>Course Progress</span>
<span id="courseProgressPct">0%</span>
</div>
<div class="course-progress-bar">
<div class="course-progress-fill" id="courseProgressFill" style="width: 0%"></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="module-list" id="moduleList"></div>
<div class="badges-panel">
<div class="badges-title">Achievements</div>
<div class="badges-grid" id="badgesGrid"></div>
</div>
</nav>
<!-- Main Content -->
<main class="main-content" id="main-content">
<header class="content-header">
<div class="breadcrumb">QES Mastery / <span id="currentModule">Module 1</span></div>
<div class="header-actions">
<div class="streak-display" id="streakDisplay">
<span class="streak-flame">🔥</span>
<span class="streak-count" id="streakCount">0</span>
<span>day streak</span>
</div>
<button class="btn" onclick="resetProgress()">Reset</button>
</div>
</header>
<div class="content-body">
<div class="slides-container" id="slidesContainer"></div>
</div>
</main>
</div>
<!-- XP Popup -->
<div aria-atomic="true" aria-live="polite" class="xp-popup" id="xpPopup" role="status">
<span class="xp-amount" id="xpAmount">+25</span>
    XP
  </div>
<!-- Badge Modal -->
<div aria-labelledby="badgeModalTitle" aria-modal="true" class="badge-modal" id="badgeModal" role="dialog">
<div class="badge-modal-content">
<div class="badge-modal-icon" id="badgeModalIcon">🏆</div>
<div class="badge-modal-title" id="badgeModalTitle">Badge Earned!</div>
<div class="badge-modal-desc" id="badgeModalDesc">Sie haben einen neuen Erfolg freigeschaltet</div>
<button class="badge-modal-close" onclick="closeBadgeModal()">Awesome!</button>
</div>
</div>
<!-- Confetti Container -->
<div class="confetti-container" id="confettiContainer"></div>
<!-- Combo Counter -->
<div aria-live="polite" class="combo-display" id="comboDisplay" role="status">🔥 <span id="comboCount">0</span>x Combo!</div>
<!-- Mobile Sidebar Toggle -->
<button aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle menu" class="sidebar-toggle" onclick="toggleSidebar()">☰</button>
<div class="sidebar-overlay" id="sidebarOverlay" onclick="toggleSidebar()"></div>
<script>
// ===== GAMIFICATION STATE =====
const DEFAULT_STATE = {
  xp: 0,
  level: 1,
  streak: 0,
  lastActive: null,
  correctAnswers: 0,
  decisionsCompleted: 0,
  synthesisCount: 0,
  badges: [],
  completedModules: [],
  perfectModules: [],
  answeredQuestions: {}
};

function safeGetStorage(key, fallback) {
  try {
    const item = localStorage.getItem(key);
    return item ? JSON.parse(item) : fallback;
  } catch (e) {
    return fallback;
  }
}

function safeSetStorage(key, value) {
  try {
    localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value));
  } catch (e) {}
}

let gameState = safeGetStorage('qesGame', DEFAULT_STATE);

const LEVELS = [
  { level: 1, title: "Novice Listener", icon: "🎙️", xp: 0 },
  { level: 2, title: "Voice Gatherer", icon: "📝", xp: 100 },
  { level: 3, title: "Pattern Seeker", icon: "🔍", xp: 250 },
  { level: 4, title: "Theme Weaver", icon: "🧵", xp: 450 },
  { level: 5, title: "CERQual Apprentice", icon: "📊", xp: 700 },
  { level: 6, title: "Synthesis Scholar", icon: "📚", xp: 1000 },
  { level: 7, title: "Meta-Ethnographer", icon: "🌍", xp: 1400 },
  { level: 8, title: "Qualitative Sage", icon: "👑", xp: 1900 }
];

const BADGES = [
  { id: "first_synthesis", icon: "🎙️", name: "First Voice", desc: "Schließen Sie Ihr erstes Syntheseszenario ab" },
  { id: "qual_curious", icon: "🔍", name: "Qual Curious", desc: "Schließen Sie das Modul „Why Qualitative Matters“ ab" },
  { id: "cerqual_initiate", icon: "📋", name: "CERQual Initiate", desc: "Schließen Sie das CERQual Framework-Modul ab" },
  { id: "method_master", icon: "🔬", name: "Method Master", desc: "Schließen Sie das Modul „Methodological Limitations“ ab" },
  { id: "coherence_king", icon: "🧩", name: "Coherence King", desc: "Schließen Sie die Kohärenz ab Modul" },
  { id: "adequacy_ace", icon: "📊", name: "Adequacy Ace", desc: "Schließen Sie das Modul „Angemessenheit“ ab" },
  { id: "relevance_ranger", icon: "🎯", name: "Relevance Ranger", desc: "Schließen Sie das Modul „Relevanz“ ab" },
  { id: "thematic_thinker", icon: "🧵", name: "Thematic Thinker", desc: "Schließen Sie das Modul „Thematische Synthese“ ab" },
  { id: "ethnographer", icon: "🌍", name: "Meta-Ethnographer", desc: "Schließen Sie Meta-Ethnographie ab Modul" },
  { id: "integrator", icon: "🔄", name: "The Integrator", desc: "Mischmethoden-Modul abschließen" },
  { id: "perfect_5", icon: "⭐", name: "Five Star", desc: "Get 5 correct answers in a row" },
  { id: "voice_of_ten", icon: "🗣️", name: "Voice of Ten", desc: "10 Syntheseszenarien abschließen" },
  { id: "decision_maker", icon: "⚖️", name: "Decision Maker", desc: "Schließe 15 Entscheidungsbäume ab" },
  { id: "halfway_hero", icon: "🛤️", name: "Halfway Hero", desc: "Complete 5 modules" },
  { id: "perfect_module", icon: "💎", name: "Perfectionist", desc: "Ein Modul mit 100 % Genauigkeit abschließen" },
  { id: "finisher", icon: "🏁", name: "Course Complete", desc: "Beenden Sie den gesamten Kurs" },
  { id: "streak_3", icon: "🔥", name: "On Fire", desc: "Maintain a 3-day streak" },
  { id: "streak_7", icon: "💫", name: "Weekly Warrior", desc: "Maintain a 7-day streak" },
  { id: "qes_master", icon: "👑", name: "QES Master", desc: "Schließen Sie die Abschlussbewertung ab" }
];

// ===== MODULES DATA =====
const MODULES = [
  {
    id: 1, title: "Why Qualitative Matters", subtitle: "Numbers can't hear patients cry", xp: 150,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "teal-bg", content: { title: "Warum qualitative Evidenz Wichtig", subtitle: "When numbers fail to capture truth" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand why quantitative evidence alone is insufficient",
          "Recognize when qualitative evidence answers questions RCTs cannot",
          "Learn from implementation failures caused by ignoring patient experience",
          "Schätzen Sie die Komplementarität von qualitativer und quantitativer Evidenz"
        ],
        tip: "Dieses Modul zeigt, warum der „Goldstandard“ RCT oft das Wesentliche außer Acht lässt."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Terms Glossary",
        subtitle: "Grundlegendes Vokabular für diesen Kurs",
        text: "<strong>Qualitative Evidence:</strong> Non-numerical data exploring experiences, meanings, and context (interviews, focus groups, observations)<br><br><strong>Qualitative Synthesis:</strong> Systematic methods for combining findings from multiple qualitative studies<br><br><strong>GRADE-CERQual:</strong> Framework for assessing confidence in qualitative review findings<br><br><strong>Thematic Synthesis:</strong> Method using coding and theme development to synthesize qualitative studies<br><br><strong>Meta-Ethnography:</strong> Synthesis method that 'translates' studies into each other to build new understanding",
        highlight: "Diese Begriffe werden in untersucht Tiefe während des gesamten Kurses."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Das HIV-Adhärenz-Rätsel", title: "When 95% Efficacy Met 50% Reality",
        text: "Antiretroviral therapy (ART) transformed HIV from death sentence to manageable condition. Clinical trials showed <strong>95% viral suppression</strong> when taken correctly. Health systems worldwide rolled out ART programs expecting to end the epidemic. The numbers were perfect. The science was settled.",
        followup: "But in sub-Saharan Africa, adherence rates averaged just <strong>50-70%</strong>. Patients who could access life-saving medication weren't taking it. Quantitative studies measured adherence rates but couldn't explain them. It took <strong>qualitative research</strong>—actually asking patients—to reveal the truth: stigma so severe that patients hid medications, pill schedules incompatible with agricultural work, fears of disclosure to partners. The RCTs proved ART worked. Qualitative evidence explained why it didn't."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "💊", title: "Szenario: Das Adhärenz-Rätsel",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Ihr HIV-Programm zeigt 40 % Adhärenz trotz kostenloser Medikamente. Quantitative Daten zeigen, dass die Adhärenz bei verheirateten Frauen im Alter von 25 bis 35 Jahren am niedrigsten ist. Ein Kollege schlägt vor, diese Bevölkerungsgruppe mit mehr Erinnerungen und Pillenzählen anzusprechen.",
        question: "What approach would best explain the adherence gap?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "More rigorous pill counting and electronic monitoring", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "In-depth interviews exploring barriers in women's own words", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Randomized trial of different reminder systems", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Statistische Analyse demografischer Prädiktoren", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! Qualitative research revealed that married women feared domestic violence if husbands discovered their HIV status. Pill reminders couldn't solve this—safe disclosure support could. Numbers identified the 'who'; qualitative research explained the 'why.'",
          incorrect: "Mehr Messungen erklären das Verhalten nicht. Quantitative Methoden können Adhärenzmuster verfolgen, aber um zu verstehen, warum verheiratete Frauen besonders Schwierigkeiten haben, müssen ihre gelebten Erfahrungen, Ängste und ihr sozialer Kontext durch qualitative Untersuchungen untersucht werden."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "dark", content: {
        label: "Die Diabetes-App-Katastrophe", title: "3 Millionen US-Dollar, die Patienten gelöscht haben",
        text: "A major health system spent <strong>$3 million</strong> developing a diabetes self-management app. Usability testing showed 95% task completion. Focus groups loved the interface. The RCT showed significant HbA1c improvement at 3 months. Leadership celebrated. The app launched to 50,000 patients.",
        followup: "Within 6 months, <strong>82% had deleted it</strong>. The quantitative metrics had measured everything except what mattered: patients found the app judgmental, the tracking felt like surveillance, and the 'motivational' messages triggered shame. Post-implementation qualitative research revealed these experiences—too late. A single round of in-depth interviews <em>before</em> the RCT could have predicted the failure."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📱", title: "Scenario: The Digital Health Intervention",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "You're designing a digital intervention for chronic disease. You have budget for either: (A) a larger RCT with 2,000 patients, or (B) a smaller RCT with 800 patients plus embedded qualitative research exploring patient experience throughout the trial.",
        question: "Which design better ensures implementation success?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Larger RCT—more statistical power means more reliable efficacy estimates", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Kleinere RCT mit qualitativer – das Verständnis des „Warum“ verhindert die Umsetzung Fehlschlag", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Neither—do the large RCT first, then qualitative if problems emerge", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Weder noch – Fokusgruppen vor dem Prozess sind ausreichend", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Die 3-Millionen-Dollar-App hatte eine statistisch signifikante Wirksamkeit. Es wurde dennoch von 82 % der Nutzer gelöscht. Eingebettete qualitative Forschung identifiziert Hindernisse und Erleichterungen während des Versuchs und ermöglicht so eine Anpassung an die Praxis. Statistische Aussagekraft bedeutet nichts, wenn die Intervention bei der Umsetzung scheitert.",
          incorrect: "Die Diabetes-App verfügte über hervorragende quantitative Daten – und scheiterte in der Praxis völlig. Die während der Implementierung gesammelten qualitativen Beweise zeigen, warum wirksame Interventionen in realen Kontexten erfolgreich sind oder scheitern. Dieses Verständnis ist für eine nachhaltige Wirkung von wesentlicher Bedeutung."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Das Scheitern der Sturzprävention", title: "Evidence-Based Exercise Nobody Would Do",
        text: "The Otago Exercise Programme reduced falls in older adults by <strong>35%</strong> in RCTs. It became a cornerstone of falls prevention guidelines worldwide. NHS England rolled it out to <strong>250,000</strong> older adults. The evidence was Level 1A—systematic review of RCTs.",
        followup: "Uptake was <strong>under 10%</strong>. Those who started, stopped within weeks. Qualitative synthesis of 23 studies revealed why: older adults perceived the exercises as 'for frail people' and felt stigmatized. They wanted to maintain independence, not be reminded of decline. Group classes felt like 'old people's homes.' The intervention that worked in trials required redesign—reframed as 'strength and balance,' delivered in community centers alongside younger adults. The qualitative evidence didn't contradict the RCTs—it explained why they couldn't be implemented."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🚶", title: "Szenario: Die Kluft zwischen Evidenz und Praxis",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Eine Intervention weist starke RCT-Evidenz auf (OR 0,65 für Stürze), aber nur 10 % Akzeptanz. Ihr Leitliniengremium muss entscheiden, wie dieses Problem angegangen werden soll. Einige Mitglieder argumentieren, dass die Evidenzstärke unabhängig von der Akzeptanz eine „starke Empfehlung“ rechtfertigt.",
        question: "Wie sollte das Gremium Implementierungsnachweise einbeziehen?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Starke Empfehlung – die Implementierung ist ein von der Evidenzstärke getrenntes Thema", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Conditional recommendation noting that implementation barriers may require intervention adaptation", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Strong recommendation with separate implementation guidance", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "No recommendation until uptake improves", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! In den GRADE-Leitlinien heißt es ausdrücklich, dass Implementierungsüberlegungen die Empfehlungsstärke beeinflussen. Eine Intervention, die niemand nutzt, hilft niemandem. Qualitative Belege zu Hindernissen sollten in Empfehlungen und nicht nur in Umsetzungsleitfäden einfließen.",
          incorrect: "Beweisstärke und Umsetzbarkeit hängen zusammen. Eine „starke Empfehlung“ für etwas, das eine Aufnahme von 10 % erreicht, ist ein leeres Versprechen. Qualitative Evidenz zu Barrieren sollte sowohl die Empfehlungsstärke als auch das Interventionsdesign beeinflussen."
        }
      }},
      { type: "stats", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Die Lücke in der qualitativen Evidenz",
        stats: [
          { value: "70%", label: "Implementation failures cite 'context'" },
          { value: "15%", label: "Cochrane reviews include qual evidence" },
          { value: "82%", label: "Digital health app deletion rate" },
          { value: "3x", label: "Better uptake with qual-informed design" }
        ],
        caption: "Quantitative Evidenz sagt uns, WAS funktioniert. Qualitative Beweise sagen uns, WARUM und FÜR WEN."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Was qualitative Beweise liefern",
        subtitle: "Understanding that numbers cannot capture",
        text: "Qualitative evidence answers questions RCTs cannot:<br><br>• <strong>Why</strong> do patients adhere or not?<br>• <strong>How</strong> do people experience interventions?<br>• <strong>What</strong> contextual factors enable or prevent success?<br>• <strong>Which</strong> components matter to patients vs. researchers?",
        highlight: "Die Frage lautet nicht „qual vs. quant“, sondern „Welche Frage stellen Sie?“"
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Der Mutterschaftserfolg", title: "When Listening Changed Everything",
        text: "Group antenatal care (Centering Pregnancy) showed mixed results in RCTs—some positive, some null. A realist synthesis combining quantitative outcomes with qualitative process data revealed the mechanism: it wasn't the <em>information</em> that helped, it was <strong>peer support reducing isolation</strong>.",
        followup: "Programs that emphasized the social component saw <strong>40% better outcomes</strong>. Programs focused on information delivery matched usual care. The qualitative evidence didn't just explain the mechanism—it revealed which version of the intervention actually worked. Without qualitative synthesis, guidelines might have recommended a hollow version of the intervention."
      }},
      { type: "refrain", theme: "black", content: { text: "Numbers measure what happened. Qualitative evidence explains why it matters." }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: Why Qualitative Matters",
        items: [
          "RCTs antworten: „Funktioniert es?“ aber nicht „Warum?“ oder „für wen?“ oder „unter welchen Bedingungen?“",
          "Implementierungsfehler sind oft darauf zurückzuführen, dass die Perspektiven und der Kontext des Patienten ignoriert werden",
          "Qualitative Evidenz deckt Barrieren auf, die quantitative Methoden nicht erkennen können (Identität, Bedeutung, soziale Faktoren)",
          "Die Frage lautet nicht „qual vs. quant“ – beide beantworten unterschiedliche wesentliche Antworten Fragen",
          "Wirksame Leitlinien integrieren beide Beweisarten für eine praktische Wirkung"
        ],
        remember: "Evidenzbasierte Praxis erfordert nicht nur das Verständnis, was funktioniert, sondern auch, warum es funktioniert und wie es in der Praxis funktioniert."
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "Warum erreichte das Otago-Übungsprogramm trotz Level 1A nur eine Akzeptanz von 10 %? Beweise?",
        options: [
          { text: "Die RCTs wurden schlecht durchgeführt", correct: false },
          { text: "Ältere Erwachsene empfanden die Übungen als stigmatisierend und mieden sie", correct: true },
          { text: "Die Übungen waren zu schwierig durchzuführen", correct: false },
          { text: "Healthcare providers didn't recommend it", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Genau. Die qualitative Synthese ergab, dass die Patienten Übungen zur Sturzprävention als „gebrechlich“ empfanden. Die Barriere war nicht die physische Leistungsfähigkeit oder das Verhalten des Anbieters, sondern Sinn und Identität. Nur qualitative Beweise konnten dies erfassen.",
          incorrect: "Die RCTs waren solide. Die Übungen waren machbar. Das Problem war die Wahrnehmung: Ältere Erwachsene assoziieren Sturzprävention mit Verfall und Abhängigkeit. Qualitative Forschung hat diese Identitätsbedrohung offenbart, die quantitative Messungen nicht erfassen konnten."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 2, title: "GRADE-CERQual Framework", subtitle: "Confidence in qualitative findings", xp: 160,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "dark", content: { title: "Das GRADE-CERQual-Framework", subtitle: "Systematisches Vertrauen in qualitative Beweise" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand the four CERQual components",
          "Erfahren Sie die Konfidenzniveaus und was sie bedeuten",
          "Apply CERQual assessment to real findings",
          "Verbinden Sie CERQual mit GRADE für gemischte Beweise Rezensionen"
        ],
        tip: "CERQual bringt die gleiche Genauigkeit in die qualitative Evidenz wie GRADE in die quantitative."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "dark", content: {
        label: "Die Geburt von CERQual", title: "Von der Meinung zum System",
        text: "Vor 2015 waren qualitative Evidenz in systematischen Reviews Chaos. Einige Gutachter fassten die Ergebnisse narrativ zusammen. Andere schlossen qualitative Beweise vollständig aus. Wenn qualitative Beweise einbezogen wurden, gab es keine Standardmethode zur Beurteilung des Vertrauens. Jede Rezension hat ihren eigenen Ansatz entwickelt.",
        followup: "Simon Lewin, Claire Glenton, and colleagues developed <strong>GRADE-CERQual</strong> (Confidence in the Evidence from Reviews of Qualitative research). Like GRADE for quantitative evidence, CERQual provides a structured, transparent framework. It asks: 'How confident are we that this qualitative finding represents the phenomenon of interest?' The framework now appears in <strong>Cochrane reviews, WHO guidelines, and NICE guidance</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "stats", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Die vier CERQual-Komponenten",
        stats: [
          { value: "M", label: "Methodological Limitations" },
          { value: "C", label: "Coherence" },
          { value: "A", label: "Adequacy of Data" },
          { value: "R", label: "Relevance" }
        ],
        caption: "Each component can reduce confidence from HIGH to MODERATE, LOW, or VERY LOW."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "CERQual Confidence Levels",
        subtitle: "What each level means for decision-making",
        checkpoints: [
          { day: "HIGH", event: "Höchstwahrscheinlich, dass das Ergebnis eine vernünftige Darstellung ist" },
          { day: "MODERATE", event: "Wahrscheinlich, dass das Ergebnis vernünftig ist, aber einige Zweifel" },
          { day: "LOW", event: "Möglich, dass das Ergebnis vernünftig, aber substantiell ist Zweifel" },
          { day: "VERY LOW", event: "Finding is not a reasonable representation; very uncertain" }
        ]
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "The Vaccination Hesitancy Review", title: "34 Studien, ein entscheidendes Ergebnis",
        text: "A Cochrane qualitative review synthesized <strong>34 studies</strong> exploring parents' vaccination decisions. One key finding emerged: parents wanted to feel like <strong>active partners</strong> in decisions, not passive recipients of expert mandates. But how confident could we be in this finding?",
        followup: "CERQual assessment: <strong>Methodological limitations:</strong> Minor concerns—most studies used rigorous methods but some lacked reflexivity statements. <strong>Coherence:</strong> No concerns—finding consistent across studies and contexts. <strong>Adequacy:</strong> No concerns—rich data from multiple sources. <strong>Relevance:</strong> No concerns—studies directly addressed vaccination decision-making in target populations. <strong>Final confidence: HIGH.</strong> This finding shaped WHO communication guidance for vaccination programs worldwide."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "💉", title: "Scenario: Assessing a Qualitative Finding",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A qualitative synthesis finds: 'Parents feared vaccine side effects more than disease.' The finding comes from 8 studies, but 3 had significant methodological limitations, and 2 were conducted only in high-income settings while your guideline targets LMICs.",
        question: "What confidence level is appropriate?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "HIGH – 8 Studien sind eine wesentliche Evidenzbasis", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "MODERATE – Herabstufung wegen methodischer Einschränkungen und Relevanz Bedenken", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "LOW—too many concerns across domains", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "VERY LOW—cannot trust findings from limited contexts", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Methodische Einschränkungen in 3/8 Studien rechtfertigen eine Herabstufung. Relevanzbedenken (HIC-Studien für LMIC-Leitlinie) rechtfertigen eine Berücksichtigung, erfordern jedoch möglicherweise keine vollständige Herabstufung, wenn andere Studien den Kontext abdecken. Insgesamt: MÄSSIGEs Vertrauen ist angemessen.",
          incorrect: "Aufgrund von Bedenken in zwei CERQual-Domänen (Methodik und Relevanz) ist die Aufrechterhaltung eines HOHEN Vertrauens nicht gerechtfertigt. Für den Befund liegen jedoch unterstützende Daten aus mehreren Studien vor, sodass SEHR NIEDRIG zu schwerwiegend ist. MODERATE erfasst die entsprechende Unsicherheit."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "dark", content: {
        label: "Das angewandte MCAR-Framework", title: "Erinnerung an die vier Domänen",
        text: "The CERQual developers offer a mnemonic: <strong>MCAR</strong>—Methodological limitations, Coherence, Adequacy, Relevance. But what does each domain actually ask?",
        followup: "<strong>Methodological Limitations:</strong> Are the underlying studies trustworthy? (data collection, analysis quality)<br><br><strong>Coherence:</strong> Does the finding hold together? Do studies tell a consistent story?<br><br><strong>Adequacy:</strong> Is there enough data? Are the descriptions rich enough to support the finding?<br><br><strong>Relevance:</strong> Do the studies directly address the review question for the relevant population/context?"
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🧩", title: "Szenario: Die Kohärenzfrage",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A synthesis finds: 'Patients prefer shared decision-making.' However, 4 studies describe patients wanting full autonomy, 3 describe patients deferring to physicians, and 2 describe context-dependent preferences. The synthesis author argues these all represent 'shared decision-making.'",
        question: "What coherence concern exists?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Keine Sorge – das sind Variationen von Shared Entscheidungsfindung", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Minor concern—normal variation within a construct", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Moderate/serious concern—the finding may conflate distinct preferences", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Cannot assess coherence without more data", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Volle Autonomie, ärztliche Achtung und gemeinsame Entscheidungsfindung sind konzeptionell unterschiedlich. Die Zusammenfassung zu einem Ergebnis verringert die Kohärenz. Die Synthese muss diese möglicherweise als separate Ergebnisse präsentieren, anstatt Kohärenz dort zu erzwingen, wo sie nicht vorhanden ist.",
          incorrect: "Hierbei handelt es sich nicht um Variationen eines Phänomens, sondern um drei unterschiedliche Patientenpräferenzen. Wenn man sie zu einer „gemeinsamen Entscheidungsfindung“ zwingt, verringert sich die Gültigkeit der Feststellung. CERQual erfordert eine Herabstufung aus Gründen der Kohärenz, wenn zugrunde liegende Daten mit dem synthetisierten Ergebnis in Konflikt stehen."
        }
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "CERQual Assessment Process",
        items: [
          "Identify each review finding to be assessed",
          "List all studies contributing to each finding",
          "Assess each CERQual component separately",
          "Make overall confidence judgment (don't just add downgrades)",
          "Document reasoning transparently in Evidence Profile"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "CERQual in Action", title: "WHO Antenatal Care Guidelines",
        text: "The WHO guideline on antenatal care used GRADE-CERQual for qualitative evidence alongside GRADE for effectiveness. For 'positive pregnancy experience,' qualitative synthesis identified what women valued: <strong>continuity of care, respectful treatment, and involvement in decisions</strong>.",
        followup: "CERQual assessment found HIGH confidence in these findings—strong methods across studies, coherent patterns, rich data, directly relevant populations. The guideline integrated this with effectiveness evidence: interventions that improved clinical outcomes but reduced positive experience were not recommended. Qualitative evidence directly shaped recommendations alongside RCT evidence."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📋", title: "Szenario: Integration mit GRADE",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "For pain management, quantitative evidence shows Intervention A is slightly more effective (GRADE: MODERATE). Qualitative evidence shows patients strongly prefer Intervention B because it preserves daily function (CERQual: HIGH). The guideline panel must make a recommendation.",
        question: "Wie sollten qualitative und quantitative Beweise gewichtet werden?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Recommend A—quantitative efficacy trumps qualitative preferences", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Recommend B—HIGH confidence qualitative evidence outweighs MODERATE quantitative", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Conditional recommendation acknowledging trade-off between efficacy and patient values", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "No recommendation—conflicting evidence prevents guidance", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! GRADE bezieht Patientenwerte explizit in die Empfehlungsentwicklung ein. Qualitativ hochzuverlässige Evidenz darüber, was Patienten schätzen, „setzt“ die Wirksamkeit nicht außer Kraft – sie informiert darüber, worauf es ankommt. Eine bedingte Empfehlung erkennt den Kompromiss an und ermöglicht die gemeinsame Entscheidungsfindung.",
          incorrect: "Neither evidence type 'trumps' the other—they answer different questions. Quantitative evidence addresses efficacy; qualitative evidence addresses patient values. GRADE-informed guidelines integrate both, with conditional recommendations when values vary or trade-offs exist."
        }
      }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: GRADE-CERQual",
        items: [
          "CERQual bewertet das Vertrauen in qualitative Syntheseergebnisse, nicht die Qualität einzelner Studien",
          "MCAR: Methodological limitations, Coherence, Adequacy, Relevance",
          "Four confidence levels: HIGH, MODERATE, LOW, VERY LOW (same as GRADE)",
          "Start at HIGH confidence, then consider whether to downgrade based on concerns in each domain",
          "CERQual lässt sich in GRADE in Evidence to Decision-Frameworks integrieren"
        ],
        remember: "CERQual antwortet: „Wie sicher können wir sein, dass dieses Ergebnis widerspiegelt?“ Realität?'"
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "What does the 'R' in CERQual's MCAR assess?",
        options: [
          { text: "Zuverlässigkeit der Synthesemethode", correct: false },
          { text: "Relevanz der Studien für die Fragestellung und den Kontext der Überprüfung", correct: true },
          { text: "Reproduzierbarkeit der Ergebnisse über Studien hinweg", correct: false },
          { text: "Strenge des Qualitativen Analyse", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Genau. Bei der Relevanz wird gefragt, ob die Studien tatsächlich die Überprüfungsfrage für die interessierende Bevölkerung/den interessierenden Kontext beantworten. Eine Studie über Impfeinstellungen in Schweden hat möglicherweise nur begrenzte Relevanz für eine Richtlinie für das ländliche Afrika, unabhängig von ihrer methodischen Qualität.",
          incorrect: "Bei der Relevanz geht es um die Anwendbarkeit – behandeln die Studien die richtige Frage für die richtigen Menschen im richtigen Kontext? Dies unterscheidet sich von der Methodik (in „M“ erfasst) und der Musterkonsistenz (in „C“ erfasst)."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 3, title: "Methodological Limitations", subtitle: "Können wir den Studien vertrauen?", xp: 170,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "purple-bg", content: { title: "Methodological Limitations", subtitle: "Bewertung der Vertrauenswürdigkeit qualitativer Studien" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand key quality criteria for qualitative research",
          "Apply CASP and related checklists appropriately",
          "Distinguish minor from serious methodological concerns",
          "Avoid common errors in qualitative quality assessment"
        ],
        tip: "Methodological limitations in qualitative research look different from quantitative bias—learn to recognize them."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Reflexivität Gap", title: "When Researchers Become Invisible",
        text: "A large qualitative study of cancer patients' treatment preferences was widely cited. <strong>127 interviews</strong> across 15 sites. But a critical detail was missing: the study never mentioned who the researchers were, what their backgrounds were, or how their perspectives might have shaped the findings.",
        followup: "This matters because the lead researcher was a surgical oncologist with known advocacy for aggressive treatment. The finding—that patients wanted 'everything possible done'—aligned suspiciously with this perspective. Without reflexivity statements, readers couldn't assess whether patients truly expressed these views or whether the researcher's framing shaped both questions and interpretations. The absence of reflexivity is a <strong>serious methodological limitation</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🔍", title: "Scenario: Missing Reflexivity",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Sie bewerten eine Studie, in der Mitarbeiter eines Pharmaunternehmens Patienten zu Medikamentenerfahrungen befragten. Die Studie berichtet ausschließlich über positive Erfahrungen. Es gibt keine reflexive Aussage darüber, wie die Unternehmenszugehörigkeit die Datenerhebung oder -interpretation beeinflussen könnte.",
        question: "How serious is this methodological limitation?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Minor—company employees may still conduct good research", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Moderate—some concern but findings may still be valid", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Serious—critical lack of reflexivity combined with obvious conflict of interest", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Cannot assess without seeing the actual interviews", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Gerade für solche Situationen gibt es Reflexivität. Mitarbeiter eines Unternehmens, die Interviews zu ihrem eigenen Produkt führen und nur positive Ergebnisse berichten, ohne anzuerkennen, wie ihre Rolle die Forschung beeinflussen könnte – das ist eine ernsthafte Bedrohung für die Glaubwürdigkeit. Erhebliche Herabstufung.",
          incorrect: "Ohne Reflexivität können wir nicht beurteilen, wie die Position der Forscher die Arbeit beeinflusst hat. Wenn diese Position ein direktes finanzielles Interesse an positiven Ergebnissen beinhaltet und nur positive Ergebnisse erscheinen, stellt dies eine schwerwiegende methodische Einschränkung dar, die eine erhebliche Herabstufung erfordert."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "dark", content: {
        label: "Das Problem der Convenience-Stichprobe", title: "When 'Patients' Means 'Advocates'",
        text: "A study of patient perspectives on telehealth recruited participants through a patient advocacy organization's social media. The finding: '<strong>Patients overwhelmingly prefer telehealth</strong> to in-person care.' The sample was 45 articulate, digitally-engaged advocates.",
        followup: "This is not 'patients.' It's a highly selected subset already comfortable with digital technology, connected to advocacy networks, and motivated to promote telehealth. The finding may be true for this group—but claiming it represents 'patients' is a serious methodological limitation. Sampling in qualitative research must achieve <strong>conceptual diversity</strong>, not just accumulate voices from convenient sources."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "👥", title: "Scenario: Evaluating Sampling",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A study claims to explore 'barriers to diabetes self-management.' Sampling: recruited from a diabetes education center, excluded non-English speakers, interviewed only those attending appointments. Finding: 'Patients report excellent access to education.'",
        question: "What sampling concern limits this finding?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Sample size may be too small", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Die Stichprobe schließt diejenigen aus, die mit den Hindernissen konfrontiert sind, die die Studie angeblich untersuchen soll.", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Convenience sampling is acceptable in qualitative research", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Language exclusion is a minor limitation", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! A study of 'barriers' that excludes non-English speakers, non-attenders, and those not in education programs has systematically excluded the people most likely to experience barriers. The finding tells us about the experience of successful patients, not about barriers. This is a serious sampling limitation.",
          incorrect: "The sample systematically excludes those experiencing barriers: non-English speakers, non-attenders, people outside diabetes education. Finding that this selected group has 'excellent access' doesn't address the research question. This is a critical sampling flaw."
        }
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Methodological Considerations",
        items: [
          "Klare Forschungsfragen, die für qualitative Zwecke geeignet sind Methoden?",
          "Sampling strategy achieves conceptual diversity?",
          "Datenerfassungsmethoden beschrieben und angemessen?",
          "Relationship between researcher and participants addressed?",
          "Analysemethoden klar und streng?",
          "Reflexivity statement included?",
          "Auf Daten basierende Ergebnisse mit unterstützenden Zitaten?"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "CASP: The Critical Appraisal Skills Programme",
        subtitle: "A structured approach to quality assessment",
        text: "The <strong>CASP Qualitative Checklist</strong> is widely used to assess methodological quality in qualitative synthesis. It includes 10 questions across three sections:<br><br><strong>Section A (Validity):</strong> Clear aims? Appropriate methodology? Appropriate design? Appropriate recruitment? Appropriate data collection? Researcher-participant relationship considered?<br><br><strong>Section B (Results):</strong> Ethical issues considered? Rigorous analysis? Clear findings?<br><br><strong>Section C (Value):</strong> How valuable is the research?",
        highlight: "CASP ist ein Leitfaden, kein Bewertungssystem. Verwenden Sie es, um Bedenken zu identifizieren, nicht um Qualitätswerte zu berechnen."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "dark", content: {
        label: "Die Analyse-Blackbox", title: "Findings Without Foundations",
        text: "A qualitative study reported that patients experienced '<strong>six distinct phases of recovery</strong>' from cardiac events. The abstract presented this as a validated model. Citations followed. It became textbook content.",
        followup: "But the methods section revealed a critical gap: no description of how the analysis produced these six phases. No coding process. No theme development. No disconfirming case analysis. The 'findings' appeared fully formed with no visible analytical work. Were these phases in the data, or imposed by the researcher? Without analytical transparency, we cannot know. This is a <strong>serious methodological limitation</strong>—findings disconnected from visible analysis."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📊", title: "Szenario: Auswertung der Analyse",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Eine Studie stellt einen „Rahmen“ der Patientenerfahrung mit 4 Bereichen und 12 Unterthemen dar. Methoden besagen: „Interviews wurden thematisch analysiert.“ Es wird kein Codierungsprozess beschrieben. Keine Beispiele dafür, wie Themen entstanden sind. Keine Diskussion widersprüchlicher Daten.",
        question: "What is the primary methodological concern?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Die thematische Analyse ist nicht streng genug", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Insufficient analytical transparency—cannot assess how findings emerged", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Framework should have more domains", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Need member checking to validate findings", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Das Problem ist nicht die Wahl der Methode, sondern die Blackbox. Ohne zu sehen, wie sich die Codierung entwickelte, wie Themen konstruiert wurden und wie mit Widersprüchen umgegangen wurde, können wir nicht beurteilen, ob das Framework Daten oder Vorurteile der Forscher widerspiegelt. Analytische Transparenz ist unerlässlich.",
          incorrect: "Thematische Analysen eignen sich für qualitative Forschung. Das Problem ist der unsichtbare Prozess: Die Angabe „thematisch analysiert“, ohne zu zeigen, wie dies geschehen ist, führt dazu, dass die Leser nicht in der Lage sind, die Glaubwürdigkeit der Ergebnisse einzuschätzen."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Gold-Standard-Studie", title: "Transparenz, die Vertrauen schafft",
        text: "Eine qualitative Studie zur Behandlung chronischer Schmerzen veröffentlichte ihr vollständiges Codierungsgerüst, Prüfpfad und Reflexivität Aussage. Die leitende Forscherin erkannte ihren Hintergrund in der Schmerzpsychologie an und beschrieb, wie dies ihre anfänglichen Annahmen beeinflusste.",
        followup: "The study showed how disconfirming cases led to framework revisions. Quotes supported every sub-theme with clear data-to-interpretation links. Two researchers coded independently, with disagreements resolved through discussion. This transparency doesn't guarantee correct findings—but it allows assessment. Readers can evaluate the interpretive process. This is how methodological rigor supports confidence."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Herabstufung wegen methodischer Einschränkungen",
        subtitle: "How concerns translate to confidence",
        text: "Not all limitations require downgrading. Consider:<br><br>• <strong>Minor concerns:</strong> Some studies have minor issues but overall pattern is strong → No/minor downgrade<br><br>• <strong>Moderate concerns:</strong> Several studies with moderate limitations or pattern of issues → Downgrade one level<br><br>• <strong>Serious concerns:</strong> Most studies have serious limitations OR key contributing study is fundamentally flawed → Downgrade one or two levels",
        highlight: "CERQual bewertet die Gesamtheit der Beweise, nicht jede Studie isoliert."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚖️", title: "Scenario: Overall Assessment",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A finding is supported by 6 studies. Assessment: Study 1 (minor limitations), Study 2 (minor), Study 3 (serious—no reflexivity, convenience sample), Study 4 (moderate), Study 5 (minor), Study 6 (serious—analysis black box).",
        question: "What overall methodological limitations assessment is appropriate?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Minor concerns—most studies have only minor limitations", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Mäßige Bedenken – Mischung aus Qualität und zwei ernsthaften Bedenken Studien", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Serious concerns—two studies have serious limitations", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Schließen Sie die beiden schlechten Studien aus und bewerten Sie sie anhand der verbleibenden vier", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Das Gesamtmuster ist wichtig. Vier Studien mit geringfügigen/mittelschweren Problemen bieten angemessene Unterstützung, aber zwei Studien mit schwerwiegenden Mängeln bedeuten, dass wir die Einschränkungen nicht einfach ignorieren können. Moderate Concern erfasst dieses gemischte Bild angemessen.",
          incorrect: "CERQual untersucht das Muster in den beteiligten Studien. Zwei Studien, die ernsthafte Bedenken hervorrufen, sowie vier bessere Studien deuten insgesamt auf mäßige Bedenken hin – das Ergebnis wird durch vernünftige Studien gestützt, basiert jedoch teilweise auf fragwürdigen Grundlagen."
        }
      }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: Methodological Limitations",
        items: [
          "Reflexivität: Erkennt die Studie an, wie die Perspektive der Forscher Ergebnisse prägt?",
          "Sampling: Does the sample achieve conceptual diversity, not just convenience?",
          "Analysetransparenz: Können Sie den Weg von den Daten zu den Ergebnissen nachverfolgen?",
          "Use CASP as a guide to identify concerns, not as a scoring checklist",
          "Bewerten die Gesamtheit der Beweise, nicht jede Studie für sich"
        ],
        remember: "In der qualitativen Forschung IST der Forscher das Instrument. Durch Transparenz beurteilen wir die Vertrauenswürdigkeit."
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "Why is reflexivity especially important in qualitative research?",
        options: [
          { text: "It increases sample size", correct: false },
          { text: "It allows readers to assess how researcher perspective may have shaped findings", correct: true },
          { text: "Es stellt sicher, dass Ergebnisse verallgemeinerbar sind", correct: false },
          { text: "Es validiert das Codierungs-Framework", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Genau. Im Gegensatz zur quantitativen Forschung, bei der standardisierte Instrumente Distanz schaffen, sind qualitative Forscher das Instrument. Ihre Hintergründe, Annahmen und Positionen prägen die Datenerhebung und -interpretation. Reflexivität macht diesen Einfluss sichtbar und bewertbar.",
          incorrect: "In der qualitativen Forschung gestaltet der Forscher, welche Fragen gestellt werden, wie Teilnehmer reagieren und wie Daten interpretiert werden. Reflexivität behebt dies nicht – sie macht es transparent und ermöglicht es den Lesern, den möglichen Einfluss auf die Ergebnisse einzuschätzen."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 4, title: "Coherence", subtitle: "Erzählen die Beweise eine konsistente Geschichte?", xp: 180,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "gold-bg", content: { title: "Coherence", subtitle: "When findings fit together—and when they don't" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand what coherence means in qualitative synthesis",
          "Identifizieren Sie Kohärenz- und Inkohärenzmuster in allen Studien",
          "Distinguish legitimate variation from fundamental contradiction",
          "Apply coherence assessment to real synthesis findings"
        ],
        tip: "Bei Kohärenz geht es nicht darum, dass alle Studien dasselbe sagen – es geht darum, ob es Unterschiede geben kann erklärt."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die erzwungene Synthese", title: "When Different Became 'Same'",
        text: "Dr. Sarah Mendez, University of Melbourne, 2019. Her team synthesized <strong>23 studies</strong> on patient experiences with telehealth. The synthesis concluded: 'Patients universally valued telehealth convenience.' This finding shaped <strong>$4.2 million</strong> in healthcare policy.",
        followup: "But a re-analysis revealed the truth. <strong>8 studies</strong> found patients valued convenience. <strong>7 studies</strong> found patients felt abandoned by remote care. <strong>5 studies</strong> described elderly patients unable to use the technology. <strong>3 studies</strong> showed rural patients preferring telehealth due to travel barriers. These weren't variations of one finding—they were <strong>four distinct findings</strong> forced into false unity. The synthesis had a <strong>serious coherence problem</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🔍", title: "Scenario: Assessing the Telehealth Synthesis",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Sie überprüfen die obige Telegesundheitssynthese. Die Autoren argumentieren, dass „sich verlassen fühlen“ nur die negative Seite der „Wertschätzung von Bequemlichkeit“ ist – Patienten, die sich verlassen fühlten, wollten einfach MEHR Telemedizin-Komfort.",
        question: "Wie sollten Sie auf diese Kohärenzbegründung reagieren?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Accept the argument—opposite findings can be two sides of one phenomenon", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Weisen Sie das Argument ab – Verlassenheit und Bequemlichkeit sind konzeptionell unterschiedliche Patientenerfahrungen", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Request more data before making a coherence judgment", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Ausschließen die „sich verlassen fühlen“-Studien als Ausreißer", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! „Sich verlassen zu fühlen“ ist nicht der Mangel an Bequemlichkeit – es ist eine deutliche Erfahrung der Verschlechterung der Pflegequalität. Das Zwingen konzeptionell unterschiedlicher Erkenntnisse in ein Konstrukt schadet der Kohärenz. Die Synthese sollte diese als separate Ergebnisse darstellen und nicht als eine erzwungene Synthese.",
          incorrect: "These are genuinely different patient experiences. Convenience relates to logistics; abandonment relates to therapeutic relationship quality. Good qualitative synthesis respects these distinctions rather than collapsing them for a cleaner narrative."
        }
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "What Coherence Assesses",
        subtitle: "The 'C' in MCAR",
        text: "Coherence examines whether the review finding is a reasonable interpretation of the underlying data:<br><br>• <strong>Pattern consistency:</strong> Do studies converge on similar themes, or contradict each other?<br><br>• <strong>Explainable variation:</strong> Can differences be explained by context, population, or setting?<br><br>• <strong>Fit between data and finding:</strong> Does the synthesized finding accurately represent the underlying studies?",
        highlight: "Coherence is compromised when synthesis forces unity where genuine diversity exists."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Good Coherence Assessment", title: "Die Diabetes-Selbstmanagement-Synthese",
        text: "Eine qualitative Cochrane-Synthese untersuchte Patientenerfahrungen mit Diabetes-Selbstmanagement. Ergebnis: „Patienten erleben Spannungen zwischen Ernährungsempfehlungen und sozialen/kulturellen Ernährungspraktiken.“",
        followup: "The underlying studies showed remarkable coherence despite different contexts. Korean patients described tension with rice traditions. Mexican patients described tension with family celebrations. British South Asian patients described tension with community events. Different foods, different cultures—but the <strong>same underlying tension</strong>. This is HIGH coherence: consistent pattern across diverse contexts, with variation that strengthens rather than undermines the finding."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🧩", title: "Scenario: Variation or Contradiction?",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "A synthesis of healthcare worker experiences during COVID-19 finds: 'HCWs experienced moral distress.' Study 1: HCWs felt guilty about infection risk to families. Study 2: HCWs felt distress about rationing care. Study 3: HCWs felt burned out from workload. Study 4: HCWs felt proud of contribution despite hardship.",
        question: "Wie ist der Kohärenzstatus dieses Ergebnisses?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "HIGH coherence—all describe aspects of pandemic healthcare experience", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "MODERATE coherence—moral distress is supported but Study 4 shows variation", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "LOW coherence—four different experiences cannot support one finding", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Cannot assess—need more studies", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! Studies 1-3 coherently support 'moral distress' through different manifestations of the same construct. Study 4 (pride despite hardship) introduces legitimate variation—some HCWs coped through meaning-making. This doesn't invalidate the finding but suggests nuance needed. MODERATE coherence is appropriate.",
          incorrect: "Die ersten drei Studien zeigen unterschiedliche Quellen des GLEICHEN Phänomens (moralische Belastung). Studie 4 führt ein zusätzliches Muster (positives Bewältigen) ein, das anerkannt werden sollte. Dies ist eine überschaubare Variation, keine grundsätzliche Inkohärenz."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Warnzeichen", title: "1,247 Patients, One Conclusion",
        text: "Dr. James Okonkwo's meta-ethnography on cancer survivorship interviewed data from <strong>1,247 patients</strong> across <strong>34 studies</strong>. The final synthesis presented <strong>one universal finding</strong>: 'Cancer survivors experience biographical disruption and reconstruction.'",
        followup: "Peer reviewers flagged the coherence problem: the 34 studies described <strong>wildly different experiences</strong>. Some survivors reported no disruption. Others never achieved reconstruction. The synthesis author had selected quotes supporting the theory while ignoring contradictory data. When forced to examine disconfirming cases, he found <strong>11 studies</strong> that didn't fit the model at all. The finding's coherence was <strong>artificially manufactured</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Coherence Red Flags",
        items: [
          "Synthesis finding covers very diverse underlying experiences",
          "Studies contradict each other but finding presents unity",
          "Disconfirming cases are absent or unexplained",
          "Very broad finding ('patients experience challenges') that could fit anything",
          "Autor zwingt Daten, die sich ihm widersetzen, einen theoretischen Rahmen auf"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚠️", title: "Scenario: The Overly Broad Finding",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "A synthesis concludes: 'Patients value good communication with healthcare providers.' Supporting studies describe: wanting information, wanting emotional support, wanting autonomy, wanting providers to make decisions, wanting shorter appointments, wanting longer appointments.",
        question: "What is the coherence problem here?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "No problem—all relate to patient-provider communication", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "The finding is so broad it cannot be incoherent—or meaningful", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Widersprüchliche Studien müssen ausgeschlossen werden", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Add more studies to reach saturation", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! 'Good communication' is so vague it can absorb contradictory preferences (short vs long appointments, autonomy vs deference). This isn't coherence—it's vacuous synthesis. The finding is unfalsifiable and therefore uninformative. Better synthesis would present distinct communication preferences.",
          incorrect: "Der Wunsch nach kürzeren und längeren Terminen ist keine Variation von „gut“. „Kommunikation“ – das sind gegensätzliche Präferenzen. Die Breite des Befundes verbirgt echte Inkohärenz. Eine sinnvolle Synthese würde diese als unterschiedliche Ergebnisse darstellen."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Coherence Done Right", title: "The Mental Health Pathway Synthesis",
        text: "A qualitative synthesis of pathways to mental health care examined <strong>42 studies</strong> across <strong>12 countries</strong>. Rather than forcing one finding, the team identified <strong>three distinct pathway patterns</strong>:",
        followup: "<strong>Pattern 1:</strong> Crisis-driven entry (12 studies)—patients sought help only after acute episodes.<br><strong>Pattern 2:</strong> Gradual recognition (18 studies)—slow awareness leading to help-seeking.<br><strong>Pattern 3:</strong> Third-party initiation (12 studies)—family/friends drove help-seeking.<br><br>Each pattern had HIGH coherence internally. The synthesis acknowledged variation rather than forcing false unity. This transparent approach <strong>maximized usefulness</strong> while maintaining credibility."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "✅", title: "Scenario: Final Coherence Assessment",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "A synthesis finds: 'Young people with chronic illness navigate identity tensions between normalcy and illness accommodation.' Studies from US, UK, Australia, and Germany consistently describe teenagers wanting to 'fit in' while managing visible treatments. Minor variation exists in HOW teens navigate this tension.",
        question: "What confidence level is appropriate for coherence?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "No or very minor concerns—strong consistency across diverse contexts", correct: true },
          { letter: "B", text: "Minor concerns—geographic variation suggests caution", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Moderate concerns—only Western countries represented", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Serious concerns—tension is too vague a construct", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! The finding shows excellent coherence—the same core phenomenon (identity tension) appearing consistently across multiple high-income Western contexts. Variation in HOW teens navigate this tension actually strengthens the finding by showing robust pattern despite individual differences. No downgrade for coherence.",
          incorrect: "Die geografische Einschränkung bezieht sich auf RELEVANZ (Anwendbarkeit auf andere Kontexte), nicht auf KOHÄRENZ (interne Konsistenz des Ergebnisses). Die Kohärenz ist stark – Studien unterstützen durchweg das Identitätsspannungskonstrukt."
        }
      }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: Coherence",
        items: [
          "Kohärenz fragt: Passt der synthetisierte Befund zu den zugrunde liegenden Daten?",
          "Legitimate variation can be explained by context—incoherence cannot",
          "Vorsicht bei der „erzwungenen Synthese“, die verschiedene Phänomene zu einer falschen Einheit zusammenfasst",
          "Overly broad findings ('patients value good care') mask genuine incoherence",
          "Better to present multiple findings than force one incoherent synthesis"
        ],
        remember: "Bei Kohärenz geht es nicht darum, dass alle Studien übereinstimmen, sondern darum, ob es Unterschiede gibt erklärt werden können."
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "What distinguishes legitimate variation from problematic incoherence?",
        options: [
          { text: "Legitimate variation can be explained by context; incoherence cannot", correct: true },
          { text: "Legitime Abweichungen ergeben sich nur aus qualitativ hochwertigen Studien", correct: false },
          { text: "Legitimate variation involves minor differences; incoherence involves major ones", correct: false },
          { text: "Legitimate variation requires at least 10 studies", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Exactly. Variation that can be explained by population, setting, or context strengthens synthesis by showing how findings apply differently. Incoherence occurs when studies genuinely contradict each other in ways that context cannot explain—forcing fundamentally different findings into one synthesis.",
          incorrect: "Die entscheidende Frage ist, ob Unterschiede verstanden und erklärt werden können. Studien, die unterschiedliche Erfahrungen zeigen, die angesichts ihres Kontexts sinnvoll sind, stellen legitime Variationen dar. Studien, die widersprüchliche Ergebnisse in ähnlichen Kontexten zeigen, deuten auf Inkohärenz hin."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 5, title: "Adequacy of Data", subtitle: "Gibt es genügend Beweise?", xp: 175,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "purple-bg", content: { title: "Adequacy of Data", subtitle: "When thin evidence supports thick claims" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand what 'adequacy' means in qualitative evidence",
          "Unterscheiden Sie Datenreichtum von Stichprobengröße",
          "Identify thin vs rich supporting data",
          "Apply adequacy assessment to synthesis findings"
        ],
        tip: "Bei der qualitativen Synthese geht es bei der Angemessenheit um den Datenreichtum – nicht nur um das Zählen Studien."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die dünne Grundlage", title: "32 Studies, 47 Words",
        text: "Dr. Maria Santos published a widely-cited qualitative synthesis on patient experiences with medication adherence. The synthesis included <strong>32 studies</strong> and produced a key finding: 'Patients experience medication-taking as a burden on daily life.'",
        followup: "A methodologist examined the evidence supporting this finding. Across 32 studies, the actual data consisted of <strong>47 words of patient quotes</strong>—fewer than this paragraph. The finding was supported by author interpretations, not primary data. The synthesis claimed rich understanding from <strong>desperately thin evidence</strong>. This is an <strong>adequacy failure</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📊", title: "Szenario: Bewertung der Datenadäquanz",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Ein Synthesebefund wird durch 8 Studien gestützt. Zur Prüfung: 3 Studien liefern ausführliche Zitate und ausführliche Beschreibungen. 2 Studien liefern kurze Zitate ohne Kontext. 3 Studien tragen nur Autoreninterpretationen ohne Primärdaten bei.",
        question: "How should adequacy be assessed?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Hohe Angemessenheit – 8 Studien sind ausreichend", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Mäßige Angemessenheit – reichhaltige Daten aus 3 Studien mit geringerer Unterstützung durch andere", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Geringe Angemessenheit – nur 3 Studien liefern reale Daten Daten", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Cannot assess without seeing the actual quotes", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Die Angemessenheit hängt von der Datenfülle ab, nicht nur von der Anzahl der Studien. Drei Studien mit umfangreicher Beschreibung können eine ausreichende Unterstützung bieten, insbesondere wenn sie durch dünnere Daten anderer ergänzt werden. Mäßige Angemessenheit erkennt sowohl die Stärke als auch die Grenzen an.",
          incorrect: "Das Zählen von Studien allein beurteilt die Angemessenheit nicht. Umfangreiche Daten aus weniger Studien können angemessener sein als dünne Daten aus vielen Studien. Drei Studien mit ausführlichen Zitaten können ausreichende Unterstützung bieten, obwohl die dünnen Beiträge anderer Anlass zur Sorge geben."
        }
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Was macht Daten „angemessen“?",
        subtitle: "The 'A' in MCAR",
        text: "Adequacy assesses whether there is sufficient data to support the finding:<br><br>• <strong>Richness:</strong> Is the primary data detailed and descriptive, or thin and superficial?<br><br>• <strong>Quantity:</strong> How many studies contribute, and what data do they provide?<br><br>• <strong>Depth:</strong> Do the data allow understanding of the phenomenon, or just mention it?",
        highlight: "Zwei umfangreiche Studien sind möglicherweise angemessener als zehn dünne. Qualität der Daten ist wichtig."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Interviewstudie", title: "Dr. Kofi Mensah's 847 Hours",
        text: "In 2018, Dr. Kofi Mensah at University of Ghana conducted a qualitative synthesis on community health worker experiences. The 12 contributing studies contained <strong>847 hours of interview data</strong> and <strong>234 pages of field notes</strong>.",
        followup: "The synthesis finding—'CHWs experience role conflict between community membership and health system demands'—was supported by extensive, detailed accounts from multiple contexts. Quotes showed nuanced experiences: the tensions, the coping strategies, the emotional toll. This richness allowed confident interpretation. The data were <strong>highly adequate</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📝", title: "Szenario: Das Umfrage-Add-On",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Eine Synthese umfasst 15 Studien. 12 sind quantitative Umfragen mit einer offenen Frage („Sonstige Kommentare?“). 3 sind eingehende qualitative Studien. Das Syntheseergebnis stützt sich gleichermaßen auf alle 15 Studien.",
        question: "What adequacy concern exists?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Keine Sorge – 15 Studien liefern ausreichende Daten", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Minor concern—survey responses add to qualitative depth", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Moderate concern—single open-ended questions rarely provide rich qualitative data", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Ernsthafte Sorge – Umfrageantworten sind keine qualitativen Daten", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! „Irgendwelche weiteren Kommentare?“ Antworten sind in der Regel kurz und dekontextualisiert – sie verleihen wenig qualitative Tiefe. Die Angemessenheit des Ergebnisses hängt wirklich von den drei eingehenden Studien ab. Wenn alle 15 Punkte gleichermaßen behandelt werden, erhöht sich die scheinbare Angemessenheit, während gleichzeitig dünne tatsächliche Daten maskiert werden.",
          incorrect: "Offene Umfragefragen erzeugen qualitative DATEN, aber selten qualitative TIEFE. Kurzen schriftlichen Antworten mangelt es an der Sondierung, dem Kontext und der Fülle der Interviewdaten. Bei der Angemessenheitsbewertung sollten Studien nach Datenreichtum gewichtet und nicht gleich gezählt werden."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Sättigungsillusion", title: "When More Studies Added Nothing",
        text: "A systematic review team kept adding studies to their qualitative synthesis, eventually reaching <strong>67 studies</strong>. They argued this extensive evidence base demonstrated high adequacy.",
        followup: "But examination revealed a pattern: the last <strong>41 studies</strong> added no new data to the findings. They repeated the same thin quotes and secondhand interpretations. The synthesis had achieved 'saturation' at 26 studies—everything after was redundant noise. Study count had become a proxy for rigor, masking that the actual <strong>unique data remained thin</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Adequacy Assessment Questions",
        items: [
          "Wie viele Studien tragen Primärdaten (Zitate, Beobachtungen) zu diesem Ergebnis bei?",
          "Sind die Daten umfangreich (detaillierte Beschreibungen) oder dünn (kurz). Erwähnungen)?",
          "Bieten Studien Kontext für die Daten oder nur isolierte Zitate?",
          "Würde das Entfernen einer Studie die Evidenz wesentlich schwächen?",
          "Entspricht die Komplexität des Ergebnisses der Datenfülle?"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚖️", title: "Scenario: Complex Finding, Simple Data",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Eine Synthese erzeugt ein ausgefeiltes konzeptionelles Modell mit 6 Bereiche und 18 Unterthemen, die „die Reise des Patienten durch chronische Krankheiten“ beschreiben. Die unterstützenden Daten bestehen aus kurzen Zitaten aus 9 Studien, die größtenteils offensichtliche Punkte veranschaulichen.",
        question: "What is the primary adequacy concern?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Unzureichende Anzahl an Studien", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Missverhältnis zwischen Komplexität der Ergebnisse und Datentiefe", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Need more diverse patient populations", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "The model should have fewer domains", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Ein Modell mit 18 Unterthemen erfordert umfangreiche, tiefgreifende Daten, um seine Komplexität zu unterstützen. Kurze Zitate, die „offensichtliche Punkte“ unterstützen, können eine ausgefeilte konzeptionelle Architektur nicht rechtfertigen. Der Befund übersteigt das, was die Daten unterstützen können – ein grundlegendes Angemessenheitsproblem.",
          incorrect: "Das Problem ist nicht die Anzahl oder Vielfalt der Studien – es ist die Lücke zwischen einem ausgefeilten Befund und wenigen unterstützenden Daten. Komplexe Modelle erfordern umfangreiche Daten, die differenzierte Muster zeigen. Kurze Zitate können 18 Unterthemen nicht rechtfertigen."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Transparent Adequacy", title: "Die Palliativpflege-Synthese",
        text: "A Cochrane qualitative synthesis on family experiences with palliative care explicitly reported data adequacy for each finding:",
        followup: "<strong>Finding 1:</strong> 'Families want honest information' — Supported by thick data from 14 studies (HIGH adequacy)<br><br><strong>Finding 2:</strong> 'Families experience anticipatory grief' — Supported by moderate data from 7 studies (MODERATE adequacy)<br><br><strong>Finding 3:</strong> 'Cultural factors shape information preferences' — Supported by thin data from 3 studies (LOW adequacy)<br><br>This transparency allowed guideline panels to weight findings appropriately. <strong>Honest adequacy assessment</strong> serves users better than false confidence."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🎯", title: "Scenario: Final Adequacy Judgment",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "A finding is supported by 4 studies: Study A (12 in-depth interviews with rich quotes), Study B (6 focus groups with detailed transcripts), Study C (ethnographic fieldwork with extensive field notes), Study D (5 brief phone interviews with minimal data).",
        question: "What is the overall adequacy assessment?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Sehr geringfügige Bedenken – drei Studien liefern umfangreiche Daten", correct: true },
          { letter: "B", text: "Minor concerns—only 4 studies total", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Moderate concerns—Study D contributes little", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Serious concerns—too few studies", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Die Studien A, B und C liefern zusammen umfangreiche, umfangreiche Daten aus mehreren Erhebungsmethoden. Der dünne Beitrag von Studie D untergräbt nicht das starke Fundament. Die Gesamtadäquanz ist hoch – höchstens geringfügige Bedenken hinsichtlich des begrenzten Beitrags von D.",
          incorrect: "Bei der Angemessenheit geht es um die Datenfülle, nicht um die Anzahl der Studien. Drei Studien mit umfangreichen qualitativen Daten (Interviews, Fokusgruppen, Ethnographie) liefern eine hervorragende Angemessenheit. Die Schwäche von Studie D ist angesichts der starken Grundlage der anderen irrelevant."
        }
      }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: Adequacy",
        items: [
          "Bei der Angemessenheit geht es um Datenreichtum, nicht um die Anzahl der Studien",
          "5 umfangreiche Studien können angemessener sein als 50 dünne Studien",
          "Complex findings require proportionally rich data to support them",
          "Achten Sie auf Sättigungsillusion – fügen Sie Studien hinzu, die nichts Neues beitragen Daten",
          "Open-ended survey questions rarely provide qualitative depth"
        ],
        remember: "Thin data multiplied is still thin. Depth beats breadth in qualitative adequacy."
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "Ein Ergebnis, das durch 50 Studien mit dünnen Daten im Vergleich zu 5 Studien mit umfangreichen Daten gestützt wird – welche ist besser geeignet?",
        options: [
          { text: "50 Studien – mehr Evidenz ist immer besser", correct: false },
          { text: "5 Studien – Rich Data bieten eine bessere Unterstützung als viele dünne Beiträge", correct: true },
          { text: "Cannot compare—different types of adequacy", correct: false },
          { text: "Equal adequacy—quality and quantity balance out", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Genau. Fünfzig Studien, in denen dünne Zitate wiederholt werden, führen nicht zu einem umfassenden Verständnis. Fünf Studien mit detaillierten, kontextbezogenen Daten ermöglichen einen echten Einblick in das Phänomen. Angemessenheit in der qualitativen Synthese bevorzugt Tiefe gegenüber Breite.",
          incorrect: "Dies ist ein grundlegendes Prinzip der qualitativen Angemessenheit: Tiefe zählt mehr als Breite. Dünne Daten multipliziert sind immer noch dünn. Reichhaltige Daten aus weniger Quellen liefern das detaillierte Verständnis, das für eine qualitative Synthese erforderlich ist."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 6, title: "Relevance", subtitle: "Treffen die Beweise auf Ihre Frage zu?", xp: 170,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "green-bg", content: { title: "Relevance", subtitle: "Wenn Beweise eine andere Frage beantworten" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand relevance in qualitative synthesis context",
          "Assess population, setting, and phenomenon relevance",
          "Identify partial relevance and its implications",
          "Apply relevance assessment to real scenarios"
        ],
        tip: "Hochwertige Beweise, die die falsche Frage beantworten, sind immer noch irrelevant."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die falsche Anwendung Beweise", title: "12 Millionen US-Dollar für die falsche Bevölkerung",
        text: "In 2017, the Ministry of Health in Tanzania commissioned a qualitative synthesis to inform community health programs. The synthesis included <strong>28 high-quality studies</strong> on community health worker motivation—excellent methods, rich data, coherent findings.",
        followup: "There was one problem: <strong>24 studies</strong> were from the United States, UK, and Australia. Only <strong>4 studies</strong> came from sub-Saharan Africa. The findings—about professional development opportunities, institutional recognition, career ladders—reflected high-income health system contexts. Tanzanian village health workers faced entirely different realities: unpaid roles, agricultural competing demands, status in traditional hierarchies. The synthesis had <strong>excellent quality but poor relevance</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🌍", title: "Scenario: Geographic Mismatch",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "You're developing guidelines for refugee mental health services in Jordan. A qualitative synthesis on 'barriers to mental health care access' includes 20 studies: 15 from Western Europe, 3 from North America, 2 from the Middle East.",
        question: "How should relevance be assessed?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "High relevance—mental health barriers are universal", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Moderate relevance—some barriers may transfer, but context differs substantially", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Low relevance—refugee mental health in Jordan has unique cultural and systemic factors", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Kann die Relevanz nicht beurteilen, ohne die Studien zu lesen", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Die Erfahrungen von Flüchtlingen mit psychischer Gesundheit werden stark vom kulturellen Kontext, der Struktur des Gesundheitssystems, Stigmatisierungsmustern und verfügbaren Diensten geprägt. Westeuropäische Erkenntnisse lassen sich nicht einfach auf Jordanien übertragen. Da es nur 2/20 Studien aus der Region gibt, ist die Relevanz NIEDRIG.",
          incorrect: "Hürden für die psychische Gesundheit variieren stark je nach Kultur und Kontext. Stigma funktioniert anders, die Dienstleistungen sind anders strukturiert und die Erfahrungen von Flüchtlingen sind unterschiedlich. Westlich dominierte Beweise haben nur begrenzte Relevanz für Flüchtlingskontexte im Nahen Osten."
        }
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Dimensions of Relevance",
        subtitle: "The 'R' in MCAR",
        text: "Relevance assesses whether the evidence applies to the review question:<br><br>• <strong>Population:</strong> Are study participants similar to the target population?<br><br>• <strong>Phenomenon:</strong> Do studies examine the same phenomenon you're synthesizing?<br><br>• <strong>Setting:</strong> Are the contexts comparable (health system, culture, resources)?<br><br>• <strong>Perspective:</strong> Do studies capture the perspectives you need (patients vs providers)?",
        highlight: "Eine Studie kann methodisch hervorragend, aber irrelevant sein, wenn sie eine andere Frage beantwortet."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Das Phänomen der Nichtübereinstimmung", title: "Adherence vs Concordance",
        text: "Dr. Fatima Al-Hassan led a synthesis on 'patient medication concordance'—the collaborative process of patients and providers agreeing on treatment. The team searched thoroughly and found <strong>45 relevant studies</strong>.",
        followup: "On analysis, <strong>38 studies</strong> examined 'adherence'—whether patients followed instructions. Only <strong>7 studies</strong> examined concordance—the shared decision-making process. Adherence assumes provider authority; concordance assumes partnership. The synthesis needed to downgrade relevance severely: most evidence addressed a <strong>related but different phenomenon</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "👥", title: "Scenario: Perspective Mismatch",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Your review question asks: 'What do patients value in palliative care?' The synthesis includes 12 studies: 8 interview patients, 4 interview family members about what they think patients value.",
        question: "Welche Relevanzbedenken bestehen für das Familienmitglied? Studien?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "No concern—family members know what patients value", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Minor concern—family perspectives add context", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Moderate concern—family members report proxy views, not direct patient perspectives", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Serious concern—exclude family member studies entirely", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! The question asks what PATIENTS value, not what others think patients value. Family perspectives are proxy data—valuable but not the direct perspective requested. Moderate concern is appropriate; the 4 studies contribute indirectly.",
          incorrect: "Family members may misunderstand or project their own values. If the question asks what patients value, studies of patient perspectives are directly relevant; proxy reports are only partially relevant."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Der Zeitsprung", title: "2023-Leitlinien aus Daten der 1990er Jahre",
        text: "A 2023 guideline on telehealth implementation cited a qualitative synthesis to support its recommendations on 'patient acceptance.' The synthesis seemed robust: <strong>18 studies</strong>, diverse settings, coherent findings.",
        followup: "But the studies dated from <strong>1995-2008</strong>—before smartphones, before widespread broadband, before video calling became routine. The synthesis described patients struggling with dial-up connections and fax machines. The COVID-19 pandemic had transformed telehealth acceptance, but the evidence base was <strong>two decades obsolete</strong>. Temporal relevance is relevance too."
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Relevance Assessment Checklist",
        items: [
          "Stimmen die Studienpopulationen mit der Zielpopulation überein?",
          "Are settings comparable (health system, resources, culture)?",
          "Untersuchen Studien das gleiche oder verwandte Phänomen? welche?",
          "Ist die Evidenz zeitlich relevant (nicht veraltet)?",
          "Erfassen Studien die für die Frage erforderlichen Perspektiven?"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🏥", title: "Scenario: Partial Relevance",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Eine Synthese zu „Erfahrungen von Krankenschwestern mit elektronischen Gesundheitsakten“ umfasst 15 Studien. 10 stammen aus Krankenhäusern, 3 aus Kliniken der Grundversorgung und 2 aus Pflegeheimen. Ihre Richtlinie gilt für die Umsetzung in der Primärversorgung.",
        question: "Wie sollten die Krankenhausstudien behandelt werden?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Full relevance—nurses are nurses regardless of setting", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Partial relevance—some findings may transfer but workflow differs substantially", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "No relevance—exclude hospital studies entirely", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Krankenhausstudien gleichberechtigt mit Primärversorgungsstudien gewichten", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! Hospital and primary care EHR use differ substantially in workflow, documentation burden, and team structure. Some findings (e.g., training needs) may transfer; others (e.g., shift handoff documentation) won't. Acknowledge partial relevance rather than assuming full transferability.",
          incorrect: "Angelegenheiten für EHR-Erfahrungen festlegen. Arbeitsabläufe, Teamstrukturen und Dokumentationsmuster im Krankenhaus unterscheiden sich von denen in der Primärversorgung. Während einige Erkenntnisse übertragen werden, werden bei der Annahme voller Relevanz wichtige kontextuelle Unterschiede ignoriert."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Relevance Done Right", title: "Die HIV-Testsynthese",
        text: "A qualitative synthesis for WHO guidelines on HIV testing examined patient experiences. The team explicitly assessed relevance for their target context: <strong>resource-limited settings</strong> in sub-Saharan Africa.",
        followup: "They found 40 studies total but classified them: <strong>22 directly relevant</strong> (sub-Saharan Africa, resource-limited), <strong>12 partially relevant</strong> (other LMICs or relevant populations in HICs), <strong>6 low relevance</strong> (HIC general populations). Findings from directly relevant studies received more weight. This <strong>transparent relevance stratification</strong> produced guidelines actually applicable to the target context."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🎯", title: "Scenario: High Quality, Low Relevance",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Eine methodisch hervorragende Studie (klare Reflexivität, transparente Analyse, umfangreiche Daten) untersucht die Erfahrungen von Krebspatienten in Japan. Ihre Zusammenfassung bezieht sich auf australische Richtlinien. Die Qualität der Studie ist HOCH. Wie sieht es mit der Relevanz aus?",
        question: "Wie sollte diese Studie zu Ihrer Synthese beitragen?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Include with full weight—quality trumps context", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Include but acknowledge transferability uncertainty due to cultural and health system differences", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Exclude—different country means no relevance", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Include only if findings match other Australian studies", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Methodische Qualität und Relevanz sind unabhängige Bewertungen. Eine qualitativ hochwertige japanische Studie kann wertvolle Erkenntnisse liefern, es besteht jedoch Unsicherheit hinsichtlich der Übertragbarkeit auf Australien. Fügen Sie die Beweise hinzu, aber seien Sie transparent über Relevanzbeschränkungen.",
          incorrect: "Qualität garantiert keine Relevanz. Die Krebsbehandlungskontexte in Japan und Australien unterscheiden sich in der Struktur des Gesundheitssystems, den Kommunikationsnormen und den Einbindungsmustern der Familie. Die Evidenz ist wertvoll, erfordert jedoch Einschränkungen hinsichtlich der Relevanz."
        }
      }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: Relevance",
        items: [
          "Hochwertige Evidenz, die die falsche Frage beantwortet, ist immer noch irrelevant",
          "Assess: population, phenomenon, setting, perspective, and time",
          "Qualität und Relevanz sind unabhängig voneinander – eine Studie kann ausgezeichnet, aber irrelevant sein",
          "Partial relevance is common; be transparent about transferability",
          "Relevance is a gateway criterion—low relevance limits overall confidence"
        ],
        remember: "Evidenz, die eine andere Frage beantwortet, wird nicht nur deshalb relevant, weil sie methodisch ist stark."
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "Ein Syntheseergebnis, das in Bezug auf Methoden, Kohärenz und Angemessenheit HOCH, aber NIEDRIG in Bezug auf Relevanz bewertet wurde, sollte welches allgemeine Vertrauen erhalten?",
        options: [
          { text: "HIGH—three of four domains are strong", correct: false },
          { text: "MODERATE—average across domains", correct: false },
          { text: "LOW or VERY LOW—relevance failure undermines the finding's applicability", correct: true },
          { text: "Cannot determine—domains cannot be combined", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Genau. Wenn Beweise nicht auf Ihre Frage zutreffen, ist ihre methodische Qualität irrelevant. NIEDRIGE Relevanz bedeutet, dass der Befund, egal wie gut er in seinem ursprünglichen Kontext gestützt wird, keine verlässliche Grundlage für Ihre spezifische Leitfrage bilden kann. Relevanz ist ein Gateway-Kriterium.",
          incorrect: "CERQual-Domänen werden nicht gemittelt. NIEDRIGE Relevanz bedeutet, dass die Evidenz eine andere Frage beantwortet – methodische Exzellenz kompensiert nicht die Beantwortung der falschen Frage. Das allgemeine Vertrauen muss diese grundlegende Einschränkung widerspiegeln."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 7, title: "Thematic Synthesis", subtitle: "Themen aus qualitativen Daten erstellen", xp: 190,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "red-bg", content: { title: "Thematic Synthesis", subtitle: "Systematic approach to qualitative evidence synthesis" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand the three stages of thematic synthesis",
          "Distinguish descriptive from analytical themes",
          "Apply line-by-line coding to qualitative data",
          "Recognize common errors in thematic synthesis"
        ],
        tip: "Die thematische Synthese schließt die Lücke zwischen narrativer Überprüfung und quantitativer Metaanalyse."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Ursprungsgeschichte", title: "Thomas & Harden, 2008",
        text: "Dr. James Thomas und Dr. Angela Harden vom EPPI-Zentrum standen vor der Herausforderung, qualitative Studien für gesundheitspolitische Fragestellungen systematisch zu synthetisieren. Die narrativen Rezensionen waren zu subjektiv. Die Metaanalyse passte nicht zu qualitativen Daten.",
        followup: "They developed thematic synthesis—a method with <strong>three transparent stages</strong>: (1) line-by-line coding of primary study findings, (2) organizing codes into descriptive themes, and (3) generating analytical themes that answer the review question. Their 2008 paper has been cited over <strong>15,000 times</strong>. Thematic synthesis became the dominant method for qualitative synthesis in systematic reviews."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Die drei Phasen",
        subtitle: "Von Daten zu Erkenntnissen",
        text: "<strong>Stage 1: Line-by-line coding</strong><br>Code every finding, quote, and author interpretation from primary studies. Stay close to original meaning.<br><br><strong>Stage 2: Descriptive themes</strong><br>Group related codes into broader themes that describe patterns across studies. Still grounded in the data.<br><br><strong>Stage 3: Analytical themes</strong><br>Generate higher-order themes that answer your review question. This is the interpretive leap—going beyond what studies explicitly say.",
        highlight: "Der Sprung von deskriptiven zu analytischen Themen ist der Punkt, an dem die Synthese einen Mehrwert schafft, der über das Zusammenfassen hinausgeht."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Kodierung Katastrophe", title: "When Categories Came First",
        text: "Dr. Elena Volkov's team synthesized <strong>34 studies</strong> on patient experiences with diabetes apps. Before reading any data, they created <strong>12 predetermined codes</strong> based on behavior change theory: 'self-efficacy,' 'social support,' 'goal-setting,' and so on.",
        followup: "Every piece of data was forced into these boxes. Patients' frustrations with app design became 'low self-efficacy.' Concerns about data privacy became 'trust issues.' The synthesis confirmed the theory—because it was designed to. It missed the most important finding hidden in <strong>23 studies</strong>: patients felt infantilized by apps designed for newly-diagnosed users when they had decades of experience. The <strong>predetermined categories blinded them to the actual data</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📝", title: "Scenario: Coding Approach",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Sie beginnen mit einer thematischen Synthese über Hindernisse bei der Krebsvorsorge. Ein Kollege schlägt vor, mit Kategorien aus dem Health Belief Model zu beginnen (wahrgenommene Anfälligkeit, wahrgenommener Schweregrad, wahrgenommene Barrieren, wahrgenommene Vorteile).",
        question: "Wie sollten Sie reagieren?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Good idea—established frameworks ensure comprehensive coding", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Start with inductive line-by-line coding, then see if HBM concepts emerge", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Verwenden Sie HBM für die Hälfte der Studien, induktive Kodierung für die Hälfte", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Reject theoretical frameworks entirely in qualitative synthesis", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Die thematische Synthese erfordert zunächst eine induktive Codierung – das heißt, Themen aus Daten entstehen zu lassen, anstatt Daten in vorgegebene Kategorien zu zwingen. Theoretische Frameworks können die spätere analytische Themenentwicklung beeinflussen, sollten aber die anfängliche Codierung nicht einschränken.",
          incorrect: "Wenn man mit vorgegebenen Kategorien beginnt, besteht die Gefahr, dass das, was die Daten tatsächlich zeigen, übersehen wird. Durch die induktive Kodierung können unerwartete Erkenntnisse entstehen. Die Theorie kann die spätere Interpretation beeinflussen, sollte aber die anfängliche Begegnung mit Daten nicht einschränken."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Exemplary Synthesis", title: "Die Studie zum gesunden Gewicht von Kindern",
        text: "A thematic synthesis examined children's perspectives on healthy eating and physical activity. The team coded <strong>17 studies</strong> inductively, generating <strong>247 initial codes</strong>.",
        followup: "Codes were grouped into descriptive themes: 'taste preferences,' 'peer influence,' 'family food rules,' 'body image concerns.' But the analytical leap was crucial: these descriptive themes generated the finding that <strong>children experienced a fundamental tension between 'being healthy' and 'being normal'</strong>. This went beyond any single study—it was the synthesis insight. Guidelines could now address this tension directly, rather than just providing health information children already knew."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🎯", title: "Scenario: Descriptive vs Analytical",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Your descriptive themes from a synthesis on medication adherence include: 'forgetting doses,' 'side effect concerns,' 'cost barriers,' 'complex regimens,' and 'feeling better stopping early.' What analytical theme might unite these?",
        question: "Which represents an appropriate analytical theme?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "'Non-adherence has multiple causes'—summarizes the descriptive themes", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "'Patients weigh medication burden against perceived necessity'—interprets the pattern", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "'Healthcare providers should address adherence barriers'—recommends action", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "'Adherence interventions are needed'—identifies a gap", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! The analytical theme identifies an underlying mechanism: patients conduct ongoing cost-benefit analysis of medications. This explains why forgetting, side effects, cost, complexity, and early stopping all matter—they're part of a coherent decision-making process. This insight can guide intervention design.",
          incorrect: "Ein analytisches Thema sollte das Muster interpretieren und nicht nur zusammenfassen (A), Maßnahmen empfehlen (C) oder Lücken identifizieren (D). Der Wert analytischer Themen besteht darin, zu erklären, WARUM die beschreibenden Muster existieren."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Das Transparenzversagen", title: "Themen aus dem Nichts",
        text: "A highly-cited synthesis on 'patient empowerment' presented <strong>five elegant themes</strong>: knowledge acquisition, self-advocacy, partnership, emotional processing, and identity integration. The synthesis shaped hospital policies across three countries.",
        followup: "A replication attempt failed catastrophically. The team found no audit trail from codes to themes. The original authors couldn't explain how <strong>127 initial codes</strong> became exactly five themes. When pressed, they admitted the themes came from a framework paper by the senior author, published in 1998. The synthesis had reverse-engineered data to fit predetermined conclusions. <strong>Zero transparency</strong> meant zero credibility."
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Thematic Synthesis Quality Markers",
        items: [
          "Line-by-line coding of primary data visible in supplementary materials",
          "Clear audit trail from codes to descriptive themes to analytical themes",
          "Multiple researchers involved in coding with disagreement resolution documented",
          "Analytical themes go beyond summarizing to generate new insight",
          "Bestätigung von bestätigten und adressierten Daten"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "ENTREQ: Reporting Standards",
        subtitle: "Enhancing Transparency in Reporting Qualitative Research Synthesis",
        text: "The <strong>ENTREQ statement</strong> provides 21 items for transparent reporting of qualitative synthesis. Key items include:<br><br>• <strong>Search strategy:</strong> How studies were identified<br>• <strong>Study selection:</strong> Inclusion/exclusion criteria and process<br>• <strong>Quality appraisal:</strong> How methodological quality was assessed<br>• <strong>Data extraction:</strong> What data were extracted and by whom<br>• <strong>Synthesis methodology:</strong> Which method used and why",
        highlight: "ENTREQ hilft Lesern bei der Beurteilung, ob Ihre Synthese vertrauenswürdig ist und repliziert."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚠️", title: "Szenario: Den Punkt verfehlen",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Eine Synthese präsentiert 8 beschreibende Themen über Patientenerfahrungen mit chronischen Schmerzen. Es werden keine analytischen Themen bereitgestellt. In der Diskussion heißt es: „Diese Themen beschreiben umfassend die Patientenerfahrung.“",
        question: "Was fehlt in dieser Synthese?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Mehr Studien zur Erreichung der Sättigung", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Die interpretative Arbeit, die umsetzbare Erkenntnisse generiert", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Statistische Analyse des Themas Häufigkeit", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Nichts – beschreibende Themen sind das Ziel", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Ohne analytische Themen ist die Synthese lediglich eine organisierte Beschreibung. Der interpretative Sprung – die Frage „Was bedeutet dieses Muster für unsere Überprüfungsfrage?“ – macht die Synthese für Politik und Praxis wertvoll. Bei der Beschreibung anzuhalten verfehlt den Zweck der Methode.",
          incorrect: "Thematic synthesis requires moving beyond description to analytical interpretation. Descriptive themes summarize; analytical themes explain and generate new understanding that individual studies couldn't provide."
        }
      }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: Thematic Synthesis",
        items: [
          "Three stages: line-by-line coding → descriptive themes → analytical themes",
          "Beginnen Sie mit der INDUKTIVEN Codierung – erzwingen Sie Daten nicht in vorgegebenen Kategorien",
          "Descriptive themes summarize; analytical themes INTERPRET",
          "The interpretive leap (Stage 3) is where synthesis adds value beyond summarizing",
          "Maintain transparent audit trail from codes to themes"
        ],
        remember: "Wenn Sie bei der Beschreibung aufhören, haben Sie zwar organisiert, aber nicht synthetisiert."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Best Practice", title: "Die Raucherentwöhnung Synthese",
        text: "A Cochrane qualitative synthesis on smoking cessation barriers took transparency seriously. They published their <strong>full coding framework</strong>, showing how 342 codes collapsed into 28 descriptive themes.",
        followup: "The audit trail was explicit: each analytical theme listed the descriptive themes it drew from, the codes within those themes, and the studies contributing to each code. Readers could trace any finding back to source data. The three analytical themes—<strong>'addiction as identity threat,' 'cessation as social navigation,' and 'healthcare encounters as missed opportunities'</strong>—each carried a complete evidence trail. This is how thematic synthesis builds credibility."
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "What distinguishes analytical themes from descriptive themes?",
        options: [
          { text: "Analytical themes are more detailed than descriptive themes", correct: false },
          { text: "Analytical themes interpret patterns to generate new understanding", correct: true },
          { text: "Analytische Themen werden von Studienautoren validiert", correct: false },
          { text: "Analytical themes require more supporting studies", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Genau. Beschreibende Themen organisieren und fassen Datenmuster über Studien hinweg zusammen. Analytische Themen übernehmen den Interpretationssprung und erklären, was diese Muster bedeuten, warum sie auftreten und was sie für die Überprüfungsfrage bedeuten. Hier bietet die Synthese einen Mehrwert, der über die Sammlung hinausgeht.",
          incorrect: "Bei der Unterscheidung geht es nicht um Details oder Validierung, sondern um Interpretation. Analytische Themen beantworten die Frage „Na und?“ indem sie Verständnis erzeugt, das über das hinausgeht, was einzelne Studien ausdrücklich darlegen."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 8, title: "Meta-Ethnography", subtitle: "Studien ineinander übersetzen", xp: 195,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "purple-bg", content: { title: "Meta-Ethnography", subtitle: "Noblit & Hare's approach to qualitative synthesis" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Understand the seven phases of meta-ethnography",
          "Distinguish reciprocal translation, refutational synthesis, and line of argument",
          "Apply translation concepts to real synthesis scenarios",
          "Recognize appropriate use cases for meta-ethnography"
        ],
        tip: "Meta-Ethnographie behandelt jede Studie als zu übersetzenden Text und nicht als zu aggregierende Daten."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Der grundlegende Text", title: "Noblit & Hare, 1988",
        text: "Sociologists George Noblit and Dwight Hare were frustrated. Educational research produced hundreds of qualitative studies that sat isolated, unable to accumulate into broader understanding. They asked: <strong>how do we synthesize interpretive research?</strong>",
        followup: "Their solution drew on translation theory. Rather than extracting 'data' from studies, they proposed <strong>translating studies into each other</strong>—preserving the interpretive nature of qualitative research while building cumulative understanding. Their 1988 book 'Meta-Ethnography' created an entirely new approach to synthesis, now widely used in health research."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Die Sieben Phasen",
        subtitle: "Noblit & Hare's framework",
        text: "<strong>1. Getting started:</strong> Identify your area of interest<br><strong>2. Deciding what is relevant:</strong> Define inclusion criteria<br><strong>3. Reading the studies:</strong> Repeated, deep engagement<br><strong>4. Determining how studies relate:</strong> Reciprocal, refutational, or line of argument<br><strong>5. Translating studies:</strong> Express concepts from one study in terms of another<br><strong>6. Synthesizing translations:</strong> Create overarching interpretation<br><strong>7. Expressing the synthesis:</strong> Communicate findings appropriately",
        highlight: "Phase 4 ist der entscheidende Entscheidungspunkt: In welcher Beziehung stehen diese Studien zueinander?"
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "The Lost in Translation", title: "47 Studien, keine Synthese",
        text: "Dr. Benjamin Okafor's team attempted a meta-ethnography of patient experiences with organ transplantation. They collected <strong>47 studies</strong> and dutifully extracted themes. Then they hit a wall.",
        followup: "Each study used different concepts: 'gift of life,' 'bodily integrity,' 'survivor guilt,' 'identity reconstruction,' 'medicalization.' The team couldn't see how to translate these into each other. After <strong>18 months</strong>, they published a thematic summary—but it wasn't a meta-ethnography. They had skipped the translation step that defines the method. The result was organized description, not synthetic interpretation."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🔄", title: "Scenario: Reciprocal Translation",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Studie A kommt zu dem Ergebnis, dass Krebspatienten eine „biografische Störung“ erleben. Studie B kommt zu dem Ergebnis, dass Krebspatienten eine „Identitätsveränderung“ erfahren. Studie C kommt zu dem Ergebnis, dass Krebspatienten eine „Lebensverlaufsunterbrechung“ erleiden. Diese scheinen verwandt zu sein, verwenden aber unterschiedliche Begriffe.",
        question: "What type of synthesis relationship is this?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Widerlegend – die Studien widersprechen einander", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Reciprocal translation—similar concepts with different terminology", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Line of argument—studies build a progression", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Cannot determine—need more studies", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! These studies describe similar phenomena using different conceptual language. Reciprocal translation involves expressing one study's concepts in terms of another's—recognizing that 'biographical disruption,' 'identity transformation,' and 'life course interruption' may be different lenses on the same experience.",
          incorrect: "Es handelt sich nicht um Widersprüche (widerlegend) oder um ein aufbauendes Argument (Argumentationslinie). Es handelt sich um Parallelinterpretationen mit unterschiedlichem Vokabular. Die gegenseitige Übersetzung erkennt diese Ähnlichkeit und schafft eine Synthese, die die Nuancen berücksichtigt und gleichzeitig die Gemeinsamkeiten identifiziert."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Successful Translation", title: "Die Meta-Ethnographie chronischer Krankheiten",
        text: "Dr. Frances Rapport's team synthesized <strong>38 studies</strong> on living with chronic fatigue syndrome. They identified key concepts from each study: 'loss of self,' 'invisible illness,' 'delegitimization,' 'illness identity,' 'biographical work.'",
        followup: "Through careful translation, they showed how 'loss of self' (one study) could be understood as related to 'biographical work' (another study)—both addressing the process of identity reconstruction. The synthesis produced a new conceptual model: <strong>'the self in chronic illness as continuously negotiated rather than lost.'</strong> This insight emerged from translation, not extraction."
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Three Types of Synthesis",
        subtitle: "How studies relate determines approach",
        text: "<strong>Reciprocal Translation:</strong> Studies broadly agree. Translate concepts between them to develop a fuller understanding.<br><br><strong>Refutational Synthesis:</strong> Studies contradict. Explore and explain the contradictions rather than forcing agreement.<br><br><strong>Line of Argument:</strong> Studies address different aspects that together tell a larger story. Build an interpretive argument from the pieces.",
        highlight: "Most meta-ethnographies use reciprocal translation. Refutational synthesis is rare but valuable when genuine contradiction exists."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚔️", title: "Scenario: Refutational Synthesis",
        xp: 35,
        scenario: "Synthese von Patientenerfahrungen mit Telemedizin: 5 Studien zeigen, dass sich Patienten durch Fernzugriff gestärkt fühlen. Vier Studien zeigen, dass sich Patienten durch den Verlust der persönlichen Betreuung im Stich gelassen fühlen. Das sind keine unterschiedlichen Aspekte – es sind gegensätzliche Erfahrungen.",
        question: "What synthesis approach is appropriate?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Reciprocal translation—find the common ground", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Argumentation – das sind Phasen in einem Prozess", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Refutational synthesis—explore what explains the contradiction", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Exclude outlier studies to achieve coherence", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Richtig! Diese Studien widersprechen tatsächlich. Die widerlegende Synthese löst dieses Problem nicht, indem sie eine Zustimmung erzwingt – sie untersucht, WARUM Patienten gegensätzliche Erfahrungen machen. Kontext-, Bevölkerungs- oder Implementierungsunterschiede können die Widerlegung erklären. Die Synthese wird reicher, wenn der Widerspruch berücksichtigt wird.",
          incorrect: "Don't force coherence where genuine disagreement exists. Refutational synthesis acknowledges and explores contradiction. The finding becomes: 'patient experience with telehealth is variable, depending on [factors that explain the contradiction].'"
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Argumentationslinie", title: "Building a Trajectory",
        text: "Dr. Khadija Mahmoud synthesized <strong>23 studies</strong> on refugee health service use. Individual studies focused on different moments: pre-migration health experiences, arrival challenges, navigation difficulties, long-term integration.",
        followup: "No single study covered the whole journey, but together they told a story. Using line of argument synthesis, she constructed a <strong>trajectory model</strong>: pre-migration health capital → arrival-related disruption → system navigation as skilled work → eventual (partial) integration. Each study contributed a piece; the synthesis built the whole. This is line of argument at its best—<strong>the whole exceeds the sum of parts</strong>."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🧭", title: "Scenario: Identifying Synthesis Type",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Sie synthetisieren qualitative Studien zum Thema Burnout bei Beschäftigten im Gesundheitswesen. Studie A befasst sich mit Stress am Anfang des Berufslebens. Studie B befasst sich mit der Desillusionierung in der Mitte der Karriere. Studie C befasst sich mit Bewältigungsstrategien für den späteren Berufseinstieg. Studie D deckt organisatorische Faktoren in allen Karrierephasen ab.",
        question: "What synthesis approach fits best?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Reciprocal translation—all about burnout", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Refutational synthesis—different career stages contradict", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Line of argument—build a career trajectory model of burnout", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Separate syntheses for each career stage", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! Studies A, B, and C address different aspects of a phenomenon that unfolds over time. Line of argument synthesis can build a developmental model of burnout across career stages, with Study D providing cross-cutting organizational context. The synthesis creates understanding none could provide alone.",
          incorrect: "Diese sind nicht widersprüchlich (widerlegend) oder sagen dasselbe anders (reziprok). Sie sind Teile eines größeren Bildes. Die Synthese einer Argumentationslinie baut ein Ganzes aus komplementären Teilen auf."
        }
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Meta-Ethnography Quality Indicators",
        items: [
          "Studien wurden mehrfach mit tiefem Engagement gelesen",
          "Schlüsselkonzepte/Metaphern, die aus jeder Studie extrahiert wurden",
          "Explizite Argumentation zu Studienbeziehungen (wechselseitig/widerlegend/Zeile von Argument)",
          "Beschriebener Übersetzungsprozess – wie Konzepte aus verschiedenen Studien zusammenhängen",
          "Synthesis goes beyond description to produce new interpretation",
          "Original study interpretations preserved while building higher-order understanding"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Alternative: JBI Methodology",
        subtitle: "Joanna Briggs Institute approach to qualitative synthesis",
        text: "The <strong>JBI (Joanna Briggs Institute)</strong> offers an alternative systematic approach:<br><br>• <strong>Meta-aggregation:</strong> Preserves original meanings by aggregating findings rather than re-interpreting<br>• <strong>ConQual:</strong> JBI's approach to assessing confidence (similar to CERQual)<br>• <strong>SUMARI software:</strong> Dedicated tool for JBI systematic reviews<br><br>JBI is particularly popular in nursing and allied health research.",
        highlight: "Choose your method based on purpose: meta-ethnography for theory-building, thematic synthesis for policy, JBI meta-aggregation for preserving original meanings."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "Meta-Ethnography Excellence", title: "The Campbell Collaboration Review",
        text: "A Campbell Collaboration review used meta-ethnography to synthesize <strong>51 studies</strong> on community responses to environmental disasters. The team published their translation table showing exactly how they connected concepts across studies.",
        followup: "The table showed: 'collective efficacy' (Study 3) was translated as relating to 'community resilience' (Study 7) and 'social capital mobilization' (Study 12). Different terms, related concepts. The final synthesis produced a model of <strong>'community coherence'</strong>—a new concept that captured what individual studies approached from different angles. This is the power of meta-ethnography: creating conceptual vocabulary that transcends any single study."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "✅", title: "Szenario: Methodenauswahl",
        xp: 25,
        scenario: "Sie müssen 15 qualitative Studien für eine klinische Leitlinie synthetisieren. Die Studien nutzen unterschiedliche Methoden (Interviews, Fokusgruppen, Ethnographie) und teilweise unterschiedliche konzeptionelle Rahmenbedingungen. Sie benötigen umsetzbare Erkenntnisse für die Praxis.",
        question: "Ist Meta-Ethnographie der beste Ansatz?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Yes—meta-ethnography works for all qualitative synthesis", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "No—thematic synthesis is more appropriate for guideline-focused reviews", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Yes—diverse methods require sophisticated synthesis", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Neither—use framework synthesis instead", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! Meta-ethnography excels at conceptual development and theory-building but may be less suitable for applied guideline questions requiring actionable findings. Thematic synthesis was designed specifically for policy/practice questions, producing findings more readily translated into recommendations.",
          incorrect: "Die Wahl der Methode sollte zum Zweck passen. Die Metaethnographie priorisiert die konzeptionelle Übersetzung und die theoretische Entwicklung. Für klinische Leitlinien, die praktische Erkenntnisse erfordern, liefert die thematische Synthese häufig direkter umsetzbare Ergebnisse."
        }
      }},
      { type: "takeaways", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Key Takeaways: Meta-Ethnography",
        items: [
          "Die 7 Phasen von Noblit & Hare: vom Anfang bis zum Ausdruck der Synthese",
          "Phase 4 is crucial: How do studies relate? (reciprocal, refutational, line of argument)",
          "Translation = expressing one study's concepts in terms of another's",
          "Reciprocal translation: similar concepts, different vocabulary",
          "Line of argument: building a larger picture from complementary pieces"
        ],
        remember: "Meta-Ethnographie behandelt Studien als zu übersetzende Texte, nicht als zu aggregierende Daten."
      }},
      { type: "quiz", theme: "dark", content: {
        question: "What does 'translation' mean in meta-ethnography?",
        options: [
          { text: "Konvertieren von Studien aus anderen Sprachen ins Englische", correct: false },
          { text: "Ausdrücken der Konzepte einer Studie in Bezug auf eine andere", correct: true },
          { text: "Summarizing each study's main findings", correct: false },
          { text: "Umwandeln qualitativer Daten in quantitative Codes", correct: false }
        ],
        xp: 20,
        feedback: {
          correct: "Genau. Übersetzen in der Metaethnographie bedeutet, anzuerkennen, dass verschiedene Studien möglicherweise unterschiedliche konzeptionelle Vokabeln für verwandte Phänomene verwenden, und die Konzepte einer Studie in Bezug auf die Konzepte einer anderen auszudrücken. Dies bewahrt den Interpretationsreichtum und ermöglicht gleichzeitig einen Vergleich.",
          incorrect: "Die Übersetzung ist hier metaphorisch – sie bezieht sich auf die konzeptionelle Übersetzung zwischen Studien, nicht auf die Sprachübersetzung. Das Ziel besteht darin, zu erkennen, wann unterschiedliche Begriffe verwandte Phänomene beschreiben, und diesen Zusammenhang explizit auszudrücken."
        }
      }}
    ]
  },
  {
    id: 9, title: "Integrating Qualitative & Quantitative", subtitle: "Synthese gemischter Methoden", xp: 185,
    slides: [
      { type: "title", theme: "gold-bg", content: { title: "Integration qualitativer und quantitativer Evidenz", subtitle: "When numbers and narratives meet" }},
      { type: "objectives", theme: "dark", content: {
        objectives: [
          "Verstehen Sie, wann und warum qualitative und quantitative Evidenz integriert werden sollte",
          "Apply different integration models (segregated, integrated, contingent)",
          "Use qualitative evidence to explain quantitative findings",
          "Navigate certainty/confidence mismatches between evidence types"
        ],
        tip: "Bei der Integration geht es nicht darum, qualitative Evidenz „so gut wie“ quantitativ zu machen – es geht darum, Fragen zu beantworten, die keiner beantworten kann allein."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Der Integrationsfehler", title: "Two Reviews, One Question, No Answers",
        text: "A WHO guideline team commissioned two systematic reviews on school-based mental health interventions. The quantitative review found: <strong>SMD 0.32, 95% CI 0.18-0.46</strong>—interventions worked. The qualitative review found: <strong>students described interventions as embarrassing and unhelpful</strong>.",
        followup: "The guideline panel was stuck. How could interventions 'work' statistically while students reported negative experiences? The reviews were conducted separately by different teams who never communicated. Without integration, the guideline panel couldn't reconcile the findings. They issued a <strong>weak recommendation</strong> noting 'conflicting evidence'—when proper integration could have explained the apparent contradiction."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🔗", title: "Szenario: Interpretation des Widerspruchs",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Returning to the school mental health example: RCTs show positive effects on symptom scores, but qualitative studies show students dislike the interventions. How might integration explain this?",
        question: "What integration insight might resolve this contradiction?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Die qualitativen Studien sind falsch – RCT-Daten sind zuverlässiger", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Die RCTs sind falsch – die Patientenerfahrung sollte Vorrang haben Statistiken", correct: false },
          { letter: "C", text: "Interventions may produce measurable symptom change while damaging therapeutic alliance and future help-seeking", correct: true },
          { letter: "D", text: "Different populations—RCTs studied different students than qualitative studies", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! Integration reveals that both can be true: interventions may reduce symptoms (quantitative) while creating negative associations with mental health help (qualitative). Long-term harm (reduced future help-seeking) may outweigh short-term symptom gains. This insight requires both evidence types.",
          incorrect: "Neither evidence type is 'wrong.' They answer different questions. Quantitative evidence shows symptom change; qualitative evidence shows the experience of receiving help. Integration asks: what happens when both are true?"
        }
      }},
      { type: "concept", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Integration Models",
        subtitle: "Drei Ansätze zur Kombination von Evidenz",
        text: "<strong>Segregated:</strong> Conduct separate qualitative and quantitative syntheses, then juxtapose findings in discussion/recommendations.<br><br><strong>Integrated:</strong> Transform one evidence type to combine with the other (e.g., quantify qualitative findings OR narrativize quantitative data).<br><br><strong>Contingent:</strong> Use findings from one synthesis to design the other (e.g., qualitative findings identify subgroups for quantitative analysis).",
        highlight: "GRADE uses a segregated model: GRADE for quantitative evidence, CERQual for qualitative, combined in Evidence to Decision frameworks."
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "green-bg", content: {
        label: "Integration Success", title: "The HIV Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis Guidelines",
        text: "WHO guidelines on HIV PrEP integrated evidence masterfully. Quantitative synthesis showed: <strong>RR 0.27 (0.19-0.39)</strong>—PrEP dramatically reduced HIV acquisition. High certainty evidence.",
        followup: "Qualitative synthesis revealed why real-world effectiveness might differ: stigma around PrEP use, daily pill-taking burden, fear of being 'outed' as high-risk. The integration insight: <strong>efficacy data couldn't be directly translated to effectiveness without addressing implementation barriers</strong>. Guidelines recommended PrEP with implementation support addressing the qualitative findings. Neither evidence type alone could inform this nuanced recommendation."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "⚖️", title: "Scenario: Certainty Mismatch",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Für eine Intervention: Quantitative Evidenz zeigt mäßige Wirkung (GRADE: HOHE Sicherheit). Qualitative Beweise zeigen schwerwiegende Implementierungsbarrieren (CERQual: HOHEs Vertrauen). Das Leitliniengremium muss diese integrieren.",
        question: "How should certainty/confidence ratings influence the recommendation?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Starke Empfehlung – beide Evidenztypen sind von hoher Sicherheit/Konfidenz.", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Conditional recommendation—high-certainty efficacy but context-dependent implementation success", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Reject the intervention—implementation barriers override efficacy", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Average the certainty levels to get overall confidence", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! High certainty that it works + high confidence that implementation faces barriers = conditional recommendation depending on whether barriers can be addressed. The integration acknowledges both pieces of evidence rather than letting one override the other.",
          incorrect: "Sie können keinen Durchschnitt verschiedener Evidenztypen bilden. Eine hochsichere Wirksamkeit und hochsichere Umsetzungsbarrieren bedeuten, dass die Intervention zwar funktioniert, aber ohne Berücksichtigung des Kontexts möglicherweise nicht erfolgreich ist. Bedingte Empfehlungen erfassen diese Nuance."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "red-bg", content: {
        label: "Die Quantifizierungsfalle", title: "When Numbers Devour Narratives",
        text: "A research team attempted to 'integrate' qualitative and quantitative evidence on patient satisfaction. Their approach: code qualitative data, count code frequencies, and include in meta-analysis as 'proportion reporting satisfaction.'",
        followup: "They converted rich narrative data into percentages: '73% of qualitative participants mentioned positive staff interactions.' This destroyed the qualitative contribution. <strong>Why</strong> patients valued staff interactions, <strong>how</strong> this manifested, <strong>what</strong> it meant to them—all lost. The 'integration' was actually <strong>destruction disguised as rigor</strong>. Qualitative evidence's value lies in depth, not countability."
      }},
      { type: "checklist", theme: "dark", content: {
        title: "Integration Questions for Mixed Reviews",
        items: [
          "Welche Frage beantwortet jeder Evidenztyp?",
          "Do findings converge, complement, or contradict?",
          "Can qualitative findings explain quantitative heterogeneity?",
          "Can quantitative findings validate qualitative transferability?",
          "What new insights emerge from considering both together?",
          "How should different certainty/confidence ratings affect conclusions?"
        ]
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "🔍", title: "Scenario: Using Qual to Explain Quant",
        xp: 35,
        scenario: "A meta-analysis of hand hygiene interventions shows I² = 89%—extreme heterogeneity. Some interventions show large effects, others show none. A qualitative synthesis of healthcare worker experiences exists.",
        question: "Wie könnten qualitative Evidenz diese Heterogenität erklären?",
        options: [
          { letter: "A", text: "Qualitative evidence can't explain statistical heterogeneity", correct: false },
          { letter: "B", text: "Qualitative Erkenntnisse zu Kontext, Kultur und Implementierung können Aufschluss darüber geben, warum einige Einstellungen erfolgreich sind und andere scheitern", correct: true },
          { letter: "C", text: "Run subgroup analysis by qualitative theme", correct: false },
          { letter: "D", text: "Heterogene Studien ausschließen", correct: false }
        ],
        feedback: {
          correct: "Correct! This is a key integration function. Qualitative evidence may reveal that successful interventions were implemented with cultural sensitivity, leadership support, or adequate resources. Failed interventions may have ignored local norms. Heterogeneity becomes interpretable through qualitative lens.",
          incorrect: "Qualitative Evidenz erklärt hervorragend, WARUM quantitative Muster existieren. Hohe Heterogenität bedeutet oft, dass der Kontext wichtig ist – und qualitative Beweise beleuchten den Kontext. Die Integration erklärt Variationen, die Statistiken allein nicht können."
        }
      }},
      { type: "story", theme: "gold-bg", content: {
        label: "GRADE Evidence to Decision", title: "Where Integration Happens",
        text: "Das GRADE Evidence to Decision (EtD)-Framework bietet einen strukturierten Ansatz zur Integration. Nach der Darstellung quantitativer Beweise zu Nutzen und Schaden enthält das Rahmenwerk spezielle Abschnitte für qualitative Beweise.",
        followup: "<strong>Values and preferences:</strong> What do affected people value? (qualitative evidence)<br><strong>Acceptability:</strong> Will stakeholders accept this intervention? (qualitative evidence)<br><strong>Feasibility:</strong> Can this be implemented? (qualitative evidence)<br><br>The EtD framework doesn't average evidence types—it gives each its appropriate role in shaping recommendations. Quantitative evidence informs effect estimates; qualitative evidence informs everything else."
      }},
      { type: "decision", theme: "dark", content: {
        icon: "📊", title: "Szenario: Komplementäre Evidenz",
        xp: 30,
        scenario: "Quantitative evidence shows breastfeeding support interventions increase exclusive breastfeeding rates (RR 1.4). Qualitative evidence identifies implementation requirements: trained supporters, protected time, cultural adaptation, family involvement.",
        question: "How should these be integrated in guidelines?",
        options: [
